# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: checker-motors-corporation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] After Japan declared in 1938 that it would be unable to host the 1940 Olympics in Tokyo due to the ongoing Second Sino-Japanese War, Helsinki had been selected to host the 1940 Summer Olympics, which were then cancelled due to World War II.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Tokyo eventually hosted the games in 1964.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Helsinki is the northernmost city at which a summer Olympic Games have been held.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] With London hosting the 1948 Olympics, 1952 is the most recent time when two consecutive summer Olympic Games were held entirely in Europe.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The 1952 Summer Olympics was the last of the two consecutive Olympics to be held in Northern Europe, following the 1952 Winter Olympics in Oslo, Norway.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] They were also the Olympic Games at which the most world records were broken until they were surpassed by the 2008 Summer Games in Beijing.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Bahamas, Guatemala, Hong Kong, Indonesia, Israel, Netherlands Antilles, Nigeria, the People's Republic of China, Saarland, the Soviet Union, Thailand, and Vietnam made their Olympic debuts at the 1952 Games.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The United States won the most gold and overall medals at these Olympics.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Inspired by the success of the Swedish 1912 Olympics, Finnish sports fans began to arouse the idea of their own Olympic Games: for example, Erik von Frenckell publicly presented his dreams of the Finnish Olympic Games at the opening of the 1915 Töölön Pallokenttä.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] As the Olympic success continued in the 1920s, enthusiasm for one's own Olympics grew, and after the 1920 Antwerp Olympics, Finnish sports leaders began planning to build a stadium in Helsinki in 1920.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Finland's main sports organizations and the City of Helsinki founded the Stadion Foundation in 1927 to get the stadium to Helsinki.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the same year, Ernst Edvard Krogius, who represented Finland on the International Olympic Committee (IOC), announced Finland's willingness to host the competition.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In 1930, preparations for the 1936 Games, which was accelerated by the launch of a design project for the Olympic Stadium.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, Helsinki was not a candidate in the first round in 1931, and Berlin won the competition, but Helsinki immediately registered as a candidate for the 1940 Games.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] World War II broke out on 1 September 1939, with the German–Soviet invasion of Poland, which also drew Britain and France to war.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Despite the aggression, the Organizing Committee of the Olympic Games continued to be optimistic about the preparations for the Games.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, the Soviet invasion of Finland on 30 November 1939, halted planning for the games.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] After the Winter War, the Organizing Committee decided to abandon the Games on 20 March 1940 due to the hostilities across Europe, the suspension of preparations caused by the Winter War, and the deplorable economic situation.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] At the meeting of the Finnish Olympic Committee on 20 April 1940, the Olympic Games in Finland were officially canceled.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the meantime, World War II had already expanded, with Germany occupying Denmark and fighting in Norway.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Instead of the Olympic Games, Finland held a Memorial Competitions for Fallen Athletes who died in the Winter War against Russia, at the opening of which actor Eino Kaipainen recited the poem *Silent Winners* written by Yrjö Jylhä.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The memorial competitions were held on the initiative of the sports journalist Sulo Kolkka.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] At the end of World War II, London was awarded the 1948 Summer Olympics after the city was originally granted the 1944 Games, which were canceled due to the war.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Helsinki continued its attempt to have the Games organized and registered as candidates for the 1952 Games.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] At the IOC Congress in Stockholm on 21 June 1947, Helsinki was chosen as the host city, leaving behind the bids of Amsterdam, Los Angeles, Minneapolis, Detroit, Chicago and Philadelphia.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Helsinki's strengths included the fairly completed venues built for the 1940 Games.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] After confirmation that Helsinki would host the Games, the "XV Olympia Helsinki 1952" was established as the organizing committee of the Games on 8 September 1947.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Its members were the Finnish Olympic Committee, the Finnish State, the City of Helsinki and 26 various sports organizations.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The mayor of Helsinki Erik von Frenckell was elected chairman of the committee, who at the time also chaired Finnish Football Association.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Akseli Kaskela, Olavi Suvanto and Armas-Eino Martola were elected Vice-Chairs.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Among them, Kaskela and Suvanto were elected on political grounds as representatives of the bourgeois Finnish Sports Federation (SVUL) and the leftist Finnish Workers' Sports Federation (TUL), Martola, on the other hand, got a former officer to lead the organization of the practical arrangements.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Other members of the Organizing Committee were Yrjö Enne, Väinö A.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Karikoski, Urho Kekkonen, Ernst Krogius, William Lehtinen, Aarne K.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Leskinen, Eino Pekkala, Väinö Salovaara and Erik Åström.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In 1948–1949, Karikoski, Kekkonen, Krogius and Lehtinen resigned from the committee, and Lauri Miettinen, Arno Tuurna and Yrjö Valkama were elected to replace them.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the spring of 1952, Ente was replaced by Arvi E.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Heiskanen and as completely new members by Mauno Pekkala and Aaro Tynell.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Erik von Frenckell was the chairman of the organizing committee and the other members were Armas-Eino Martola (competition director), Yrjö Valkama (sports director), Olavi Suvanto (maintenance director), Akseli Kaskela, Aarne K.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In addition, the head of the central office Kallio Kotkas and the head of information Eero Petäjäniemi were involved in the competition organization.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The international political atmosphere was tense when the Helsinki Olympics were held.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] When the IOC held its meeting in Vienna in 1951, many difficult topics were on the agenda.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Cold War was under way, and the situation between Israel and Arab countries, divided Germany had to be addressed as a team, and the Chinese Civil War, with the Chinese Communist Party winning, forming the People's Republic of China and the Republic of China government exiled to Taiwan.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Four years earlier, Japan was not invited to the London Olympics from the losing states of the Second World War.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic Committee of Israel had not yet been recognized, and a successor to the German Olympic Committee, which had been dissolved during World War II, had not yet been established, but all these countries already participated in the Helsinki Games, as did Saarland.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Cold War affected the participation of both the United States and the Soviet Union in the Games.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The participation of the United States in the Games was decided only after the country had received an assessment of the political situation in Finland from its embassy in Helsinki.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Soviet Union was accepted as a member of the IOC in May 1951, and in December of the same year the country accepted the invitation to the competition, as the country's athletes were in medal condition.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Although the Soviet leadership had previously considered the Games a bourgeois event, the Helsinki Games held propaganda value.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the Soviet Union, billions of rubles were spent on coaching athletes in just one year.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Soviet Union planned to fly its athletes every day between Leningrad and Helsinki.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Another option was for Soviet athletes to stay in the Soviet Porkkalanniemi garrison.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, Finland required that all competitors stay in the Olympic village.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] As a compromise solution for the Eastern Bloc athletes, a second Olympic village was established in Espoo, Otaniemi as Soviet leaders wanted them to avoid contact with Western athletes.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Joseph Stalin allowed Soviet athletes to enter the 1952 Summer Olympics because he was sure that they would win the most medals.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, American athletes secured more gold and total medals and Stalin afforded more resources for the advancement of elite athletes in the Soviet Union in the build-up to the 1956 Summer Olympics.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The 1952 Games were also threatened with cancellation due to the deteriorating world situation.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Korean War had begun in 1950, which also caused concern in the organizing committee.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] At Von Frenckell's suggestion, the organizing committee decided to take out Lloyd's of London war insurance.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Most of the venues for the competitions were completed prior to the 1940s in anticipation of successful bid attempts, but some expansion and refurbishment work was needed, including the construction of additional stands at the Olympic and Swimming Stadium.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A residential area, Kisakylä (Olympic Village) was built south of Käpylä's Koskelantie to accommodate competitors.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The area, which was built close to the 1940 Olympics, was already the residence of the people of Helsinki at that time.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Just below the opening, the competition area was completed for the use of visitors Kumpula Outdoor Swimming Pool.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Female athletes got their own race village from the Nursing College in Meilahti.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The athletes of the Soviet-led Eastern Bloc stayed in the Teekkarikylä in Otaniemi.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Finnish team lived on the premises of the Santahamina Army School (later the Cadet School, now the National Defence University).
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The City of Helsinki prepared for the Olympics by building a new airport in Seutula (now Helsinki-Vantaan lentoasema), 11-story Hotelli Palace, and the Olympic Pier in South Harbor.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A large electric scoreboard was procured.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] It attracted international attention because it represented the top of its time in the scoreboard field both in terms of its system and its technology.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] OMEGA debuted the OMEGA Time Recorder in Helsinki.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] This all-new quartz clock not only timed the events but also printed out the results.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] This breakthrough technology allowed official Olympic times to be accurate to 1/100 of a second.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] As a result, the company received the prestigious Croix du Mérite Olympique award for their efforts.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In 1950 cable television was tried for the first time in Finland, in the 1952 Olympics people could watch TV sending from the stadium through coaxial cable to Stockmann department store window.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Helsinki paved tens of kilometers of roads, and a myriad of houses were painted.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The city's first traffic lights were installed at the intersection of Aleksanterinkatu and Mikonkatu in October 1951.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Palace Hotel and Vaakuna Hotel among others, were completed for the needs of the guests.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, due to the relatively low number of hotels in the city, tent villages were built for tourists in Lauttasaari and Seurasaari, among others.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, the preparations for accommodation turned out to be considerably oversized; at its best, the occupancy rate of the 6,000-seat tent village in Lauttasaari had an occupancy of only 8 per cent.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] With the support of the Olympia 1952 committee, Finland's first mini golf courses were completed to entertain guests.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The International Olympic Committee had declared in 1950 that it did not have an official Olympic anthem, but that the organizers could decide their own anthems.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] An anthem competition was held in Finland.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the spring of 1951, a poetry competition was announced, which was surprisingly won by an unknown teacher candidate, Niilo Partanen.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Second and third came the well-known poets Toivo Lyy and Heikki Asunta.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] These winning poems were allowed to be used in the composition competition.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The selection of the 51 compositions by a jury chaired by Jouko Tolonen was also a surprise.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] When the winner was announced on 17 March 1952, an unknown teacher Jaakko Linjama was revealed behind the nickname, who had used Lyy's lyrics in his Olympic Hymn.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The nicknames of the other contestants were not opened.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] This caused a stir, and Arijoutsi, among others, doubted that the victory of the unknown would go to the honor of well-known composers.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] There were well-known members in the competition.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The voters had identified the composing style of Uuno Klami and Aarre Merikanto, among others.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The only Finnish composer who congratulated Linjamaa was Jean Sibelius, who did not take part in the anthem.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic torch was transported by land from Olympia to Athens from where fire's journey continued in a miner's lamp donated by the Saar Olympic Committee on a SAS plane to Aalborg, Denmark.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The glass cover surrounding the lamp was designed by the artist Sakari Tohka.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic torch itself was designed by the artist Aukusti Tuhka.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] From Denmark, the torchlight continued by running, cycling, riding, rowing and paddling to Copenhagen, from where the fire was transported by ferry to Sweden to Malmö.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The journey of the torch across Sweden was carried to Haparanda by 700 messengers, from where it continued to the Finnish side in Tornio.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] On the Finnish-Swedish border bridge, the torch was received by Ville Pörhölä, who brought it to Tornio sports ground.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic torch from Tornio, Greece, was connected to Pallastunturi on 6 July 1952 where it ignited the "midnight sun fire".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In reality, the Pallastunturi fire was lit with liquefied petroleum gas, because the night in July was cloudy at that time and it was not possible to use the sun as a lighter.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] From Tornio, the torch traveled through Finland to Helsinki.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] It was transported by more than 1,200 people.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Initially, the aim was to transport fire to Helsinki via the Soviet Union, but the matter was not settled through diplomacy by the deadline.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The journey covered a total of 7,870 kilometres on the journey that began on 25 June and ended on 19 July 1952.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The actual Olympic flame was lit for the Olympic Stadium.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The opening ceremony of the Helsinki Olympics was held on 19 July.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Although the weather was rainy and chilly and the Olympic Stadium had no roof but on top of the main auditorium, the stadium was full with 70,435 spectators.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The inaugural march had a record 5,469 people from 67 countries.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] After the march, the countries organized themselves into the central lawn, and the chairman of the organizing committee, Erik von Frenckell, spoke in Finnish, Swedish, French and English.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Paasikivi gave the opening speech, which was the shortest in Olympic history and contained a mistake: it was not the "Fifteenth Olympic Games", but the XV Olympic Games and the 12th World Olympics, due to the 1916, 1940 and 1944 races had been canceled.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The speech was followed by the raising of the Olympic flag and the *Olympic fanfare* composed by Aarre Merikanto.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic flame was lit by running heroes Paavo Nurmi (to the stadium) and Hannes Kolehmainen (to the stadium tower).
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] When Paavo Nurmi was announced to arrive at the stadium, athletes from the participating countries deviated from the formation to see the legend better.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Only the lines of the Soviet Union and Finland remained in the line.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] After the Olympic flame was lit, the Archbishop Ilmari Salomies was due to say a prayer, but German Barbara Rotbraut-Pleyer, nicknamed "White Angel of the Games", had jumped from the auditorium onto the track and ran straight to the speaker's seat.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Organizers quickly removed Pleyer, who had time to say just a few words into the microphone.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Pleyer's purpose was to proclaim a message of peace.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Heikki Savolainen, a gymnast who was competing in his fifth consecutive Olympic games, swore the Olympic oath on behalf of the athletes.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] There were 4,925 athletes from 69 countries, with the Soviet Union making its Olympic debut and Germany participating for the first time since World War II.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of 149 events were held in 17 different sports.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The most-medalling athletes of the Games were Viktor Chukarin of the Soviet Union, who won four gymnastics Olympic gold medals, and Czechoslovakia's Emil Zátopek, who won three track golds.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The United States won the most gold and total medals, with 40 and 76.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The host country, Finland, had 6 gold, 3 silver and 13 bronze medals.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Shooting was competed in seven events, six of which (rifle sports) were conducted at the Malmi Shooting Range in moderately difficult wind conditions.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Tough results were still fired in Helsinki, as the top four deer shooting broke world records.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] World records for knee position were also broken in free and small rifles.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Shotgun shooting took place at the Huopalahti shooting range.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Ten countries took medals from the shooting.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Norway was the only country to win two gold medals, with the Soviet Union winning the most medals.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Boris Andreyev was the only Soviet shooter to win two multiple medals.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A Finnish winner was already celebrated in a miniature rifle when Vilho Ylönen had time to play on the radio *Björneborgarnas marsch*.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, in an hour-long countdown, the Norwegian Erling Asbjørn Kongshaug was declared the winner of the competition.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The football tournament started even before the official opening, as the one-piece qualifiers took place on 15–16 July in Kotka, Lahti, Tampere, Turku and Helsinki.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] There were 27 countries registered for the tournament, but Saarland and Mexico dropped out before the Games.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Hungary *Golden Team* won the gold when it knocked down the Yugoslavia in the final with a score of 2–0.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the final, the Olympic Stadium had 58 553 paid spectators, the largest number of spectators in Finland watching a football match.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The first meeting between the Soviet Union and Yugoslavia in football is still amongst the most famous matches.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] On the political level, the Soviet leader Joseph Stalin and the Yugoslav leader Josip Tito split in 1948, which resulted in Yugoslavia being excluded from the Communist Information Bureau.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The origin of the conflict was Tito's refusal to submit to Stalin's interpretations and visions of politics and in process becoming a Soviet satellite state.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Before the match, both Tito and Stalin sent telegrams to their national teams, which showed just how important it was for the two head of states.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Yugoslavia led 5–1, but a Soviet comeback in the last 15 minutes resulted in a 5–5 draw.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The match was replayed, Yugoslavia winning 3–1.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The defeat to the archrivals hit Soviet football hard, and after just three games played in the season, CSKA Moscow, who had made up most of the USSR squad, was forced to withdraw from the league by Joseph Stalin and later disbanded.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Furthermore, Boris Arkadiev, who coached both USSR and CDKA, was stripped of his Merited Master of Sports of the USSR title.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] 23 teams entered basketball, ten of which made it directly to the actual tournament.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The remaining 13 countries took the final six places in the Olympic tournament before the official opening of the Olympic Games.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In basketball, the gold medal was won by the United States, who defeated Soviet Union in the final 36–25.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The final match was relatively slow-paced, as the Soviet Union tried to keep up with the United States by freezing the game.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The United States had already clearly beat the Soviet Union 86–58 earlier in the tournament.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The bronze was won by Uruguay, who also organized a mass battle after being dissatisfied with the referee's work.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Field hockey was included in the Helsinki Olympic Games in the range of sports on the condition that a maximum of 12 teams register for the Games.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the end, 16 teams applied for the competition, from which the International Field Hockey Federation selected 12 countries to participate in the competition venue.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Eventually, four countries dropped out of the Games, so the remaining 12 teams that had applied for the competition were able to take part in the Olympic tournament.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The tournament started with two rounds before the Games opened, and the final match was held on 24 July.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] India and Netherlands met in the Velodrome final, with India winning its fifth consecutive gold under captaincy of Kunwar Digvijay Singh with a score of 6–1.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Canoeing competitions were held Taivallahti 27–28 July.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] There were a total of 159 participants in eight men's and women's only races, coming from 21 countries.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Canoeing was a celebration in Finland, as four of the nine sports went to the host country.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In addition, the Finns took one silver and a bronze.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The double gold medalists were Kurt Wires and Yrjö Hietanen who won the kayak duo's 1,000 and 10,000 meters.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the only women's sport, the 500-meter kayak unit, gold was taken by Sylvi Saimo, who was the first Finnish female gold medalist in the summer competitions.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The second most successful country in kayaking was Sweden, which won one gold and three silver.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Helsinki Olympics fencing competitions were held on the Espoo side of the Westend Tennis Hall.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The men competed with Épée, sabre and foil in both personal competition and team competition.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The women had only a personal competition for foil in the program.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] There were 250 men and 37 women from 32 countries.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Italy, Hungary and France were, as usual, the best fencing countries and took all the gold medals.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of six countries reached medals.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Mangiarot brothers Edoardo and Dario took a double victory over the film.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Hungarian swordsmen won a triple victory over the preserve.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Modern pentathlon Olympic competitions was held at Ahvenisto Hämeenlinna.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of 51 competitors from 19 countries entered the sport.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] For the first time in Olympic history, the sport also included a team competition.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Sweden, Hungary and Finland shared the medals.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Sweden's Lars Hall won the individual competition, and Hungary was the best in the team competition.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Before Hall, all Olympic winners of the sport have been officers.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, Hall was a carpenter by profession.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Töölö Sports Hall held Olympic boxing between 28 July to 2 August in ten weight classes.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The most successful boxing country was the United States, which won five gold.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Soviet Union won the most medals, but its boxers did not win a single championship.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the middle series, the American Floyd Patterson knocked out Romanian Vasile Tiță in a record-breaking 42 seconds.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The American Norvel Lee, who won the heavyweight series, was awarded as the most technical boxer in the Games.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the heavyweight series Ed Sanders got gold when the Swedish Ingemar Johansson was rejected for his passivity.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Johansson did not receive his silver medal until 1982.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Wrestling was held in Helsinki in eight weight classes in both Greco-Roman wrestling and freestyle wrestling.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] All finals were held in the larger Exhibition Hall I, but freestyle wrestling events were held in the smaller Exhibition Hall II.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Free button competitions were held on 20–23 July, and Greco-Roman wrestling matches took place on 24–27 July.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The most successful wrestling country was the Soviet Union, whose athletes won six gold and a total of ten medals in the sport.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Sweden dominated free wrestling and received the second highest number of medals in wrestling overall.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The overwhelming athlete in wrestling was the Soviet Johannes Kotkas, who competed in the heavy series of Greco-Roman wrestling.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] He managed to beat all his opponents in less than five minutes.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic weightlifting competition was held in seven weight classes with 141 competitors.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Initially, there were to be only six weight classes, but a light heavyweight series was also added to the program, as a result of which the weight limit for the heavyweight series increased from 82.5 kilograms to 90 kilograms.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The addition of the new weight class took place so late that there was no time to change the race program.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Weightlifting was carried out according to plan at the Exhibition Hall on 25–27 July.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] All seven gold medals were awarded to athletes from the United States and the Soviet Union.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Soviets won a total of seven medals, but the Americans took four championships, while the Soviets only took three.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of five world records were set in weightlifting.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the heavyweight series John Davis continued his superiority, Davis had not lost a single event since 1938 and continued with his victory in Helsinki as well.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The competition took place in the waters of Helsinki from 20 to 28 May in five different categories.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Larger boats sailed in front of Harmaja lighthouse island, and the Finn race was held near Liuskasaari.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of 93 crews from 29 countries took part in the competition.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The United States, Norway and Sweden took three medals.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The United States was the only country to reach two gold medals in sailing.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the Finn that developed from the Firefly class, the Danish Paul Elvstrøm won the overwhelming championship.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The gold medal was the second in Elvstrøm's career.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] He later became the first athlete to win the same sport four times in a row (individual disciplines).
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In cycling, medals were awarded in six sports, four for track cycling and two for road racing.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In total, 214 competitors from 36 countries took part in the cycling.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Track cycling competitions were held from 29 to 31 July and road driving on 2 August.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of seven countries collected medals and gold medals went to Italy, Australia and Belgium.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Italy was the most successful country with five medals.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Two gold medals went to Australian Russell Mockridge, who won the championship in the kilometer time trial and with his partner in tandem racing, and the Belgian André Noyelle, who won the 190 kilometer road race personal competition and team competition.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Equestrian events were competed in dressage, Eventing and show jumping in person and in team competition in a total of six sports.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Eight countries won medals in horseback riding, and Sweden was by far the most successful country.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Swedes won both races in both dressage and field riding.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] For the events in first time non-military officers including women were allowed to take part in dressage events in Helsinki.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In a show jumping, Danish Lis Hartel, paralyzed from her knees down, was the first woman to win a riding medal after finishing second in the Olympics.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Rowers competed in seven sports from 20 to 23 July.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The competition was held in Meilahti, as Taivallahti, where the canoeing competitions took place, was too open to the sea breeze.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] There were a total of 409 entrants from 33 countries.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Representatives from fourteen countries won medals, and only American rowers won two gold medals.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The youngest Olympic winner of the Games was seen in Rowing.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the coxswain duo, the French winning team included 14 years old Bernard Malivoire.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Diving competed in a total of four men's and women's events.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The United States led the events, as nine of the 12 medals in the distribution went to the country.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In addition to the United States, only France, Mexico and Germany won medals in the sport.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Patricia McCormick won Olympic gold in the women's events from both the three-meter springboard and the ten-meter floor jump.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] At the Helsinki Swimming Stadium men competed in six sports and women in five sports.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] High-level competitions were held from July 25 to 2 August.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Summer Olympics in London had resulted in significant progress in the sport, and every Olympic record was broken in each event.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Americans dominated men's events and the Hungarians dominated women.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Ford Konno was the most successful swimmer with two gold medals and one silver.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the women's events Katalin Szőke won two gold medals and Éva Novák two silver in addition to the gold medal.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The only world record in the Games was set by the Hungarian women's 4 × 100 meter freestyle message team.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Helsinki Olympics, was the last instance where competitors could participate in Breaststroke in the butterfly stroke.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the men's events, no athlete swimming in the breaststroke style made it to the finals.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of 21 countries took part in the water polo tournament.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The initial series of the Games was to be played in the offshore pools, but due to the coolness of the water, the International Swimming Federation ordered all the matches to be played at the Swimming Stadium.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Because of this, some of the matches in the first series had to be played as early as six in the morning.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The water polo championship was decided in the final block, where the four teams faced each other once.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Hungary and Yugoslavia ended in a draw after winning two other matches and playing 2–2 each other.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Hungary won gold with a better goal difference.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The 1952 Olympic gymnastics was dominated by the Soviet Union, which had already been an established gymnastics power by 1952.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The USSR's athletes won nine gold medals and took a total of 22 medals.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Finland, Germany and Switzerland, who previously dominated the gymnastics at the Olympics, were content with more modest success.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of fifteen medals were awarded, eight in men's events and seven in women's events.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The most personal medals in gymnastics were taken by Viktor Chukarin in the men's events and Maria Gorokhovskaya in the women's events.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Gorokhovskaya won medals in every women's sport.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Her seven-medal catch (two gold and five silver) was a record for one women's Olympics.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Athletics was competed in 33 sports, 24 for men and 9 for women.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] By far the most successful state was the United States, which won 31 medals, nine of which were gold.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Soviet Union reached 17 medals, but won only two championships, and the eight-medal country Germany was left without first places.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The second medalist was Czechoslovakia, with four of the five medals being the brightest.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Emil Zátopek won the 5,000 and 10,000 meters, as well as the marathon, which he had never run before, all in new Olympic record times.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] On the women's side, the Australian Marjorie Jackson won the 100 and 200 meter runs.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the triple jump Adhemar Ferreira da Silva broke the old world record four times.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the decathlon, Bob Mathias made a new ME and took the victory with a total score of 7,887 points, more than 900 points to the next.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Josy Barthel of Luxembourg pulled a major surprise by winning the 1500 m.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] According to the Olympic rules, the organizer of the Games was allowed to choose between two types of demonstration sports, one from abroad and one from Finland.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In connection with the Helsinki Games, a handball and pesäpallo (Finnish baseball) match was held.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the handball match of the Games, Sweden and Denmark faced at the Olympic Stadium.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The level of playing outside was modest due to heavy rain.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The pesäpallo match was also played at the Olympic Stadium.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Finnish Baseball Federation and Finnish Workers' Sports Federation teams competed in the event.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Baseball Federation won the match 8–4.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] During the breaks in both shows, the audience was entertained by the performances of Finnish male and female gymnasts.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] With an annual average temperature of 5.9 °C (42.6 °F), Helsinki is one of the coldest cities to have hosted the Summer Olympics.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Most of the competition venues were located in Helsinki Metropolitan Area.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Modern pentathlon and some field hockey games were held in Hämeenlinna and some football games by Tampere, Lahti, Kotka and Turku.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The main arena was the Olympic Stadium, which hosted the opening and closing ceremonies, athletics competitions, football semi-finals and finals, as well as the show jumping competition "Prix des Nations" were held.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The stadium was built for the 1940 Olympics and opened as early as 1938, but had suffered under the bombing of World War II.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] It had to undergo expansion and refurbishment work.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The concrete auditorium section was expanded and a new temporary wooden auditorium was built on the south and north curves and on the east side, which increased the Stadium's audience capacity to about 70,000.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The swimming competitions were held at Helsinki Swimming Stadium, located just a few hundred meters east of the Olympic Stadium and with three pools: a racing, diving and children's pool.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The swimming stadium could accommodate about 9,500 spectators, while the wooden eastern and standing stands for the Games could accommodate a total of about 6,000 people.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Fair Hall near the stadiums (now Töölö Sports Hall) many of the indoor events were held in two separate halls.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the bigger hall, men competed in gymnastics, wrestling and boxing.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The smaller hall hosts the women's gymnastics, freestyle wrestling, weightlifting and basketball finals.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Basketball first round matches were played at Tennis Palace and fencing competitions were held at the Westend tennis center in Espoo.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The shooting events took place at the Malmi shooting range 11 kilometers from the center of Helsinki, with the exception of clay pigeon shooting.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Clay pigeon shooting was performed on the Finnish Hunters' Association track Huopalahti.Ruskeasuo competed in dressage as well as in Tali and Laakso in field riding.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Töölö Rowing Stadium was built for rowing and canoeing events one kilometer from Taivallahti.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, the place was not accepted as a place for rowing competitions, as it was open to the sea breeze.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The rowing took place in Meilahti about three kilometers from the Stadium.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The place was considerably more sheltered than Taivallahti.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Harmaja, a lighthouse island a couple of kilometers off the coast of Helsinki, was the starting and finishing area for larger sailing classes.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Finn was the starting and finish point of the race Liuskasaari close to the coast.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Marathon running route was north of the Stadium to Käpylä, Pakinkylä, Tuomarinkylä, Vantaa, Tikkurila and Korso.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In Tuusula, Mätäkivenmäki there was a turning point from which the runners set off on their way back to the Stadium.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The 50-kilometer walk was organized along the same route.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A memorial stone was later erected at the turning point along Old Tuusulantie.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A swimming stadium was built in Hämeenlinna for Ahvenisto for the pentathlon.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The other four pentathlon events were also held in the vicinity of Ahvenisto.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of 69 nations participated in these Games, up from 59 in the 1948 Games.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Thirteen nations made their first Olympic appearance in 1952: The Bahamas, the People's Republic of China, Gold Coast (now Ghana), Guatemala, Hong Kong, Indonesia, Israel, Netherlands Antilles, Nigeria, the Soviet Union (USSR), Thailand, and Vietnam.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Japan and Germany were both reinstated and permitted to send athletes after being banned for 1948 for their instigation of World War II.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Due to the division of Germany, German athletes from Saar entered a separate team for the only time.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Only West Germany would provide athletes for the actual German team, since East Germany refused to participate in a joint German team.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Romania returned to the games in this edition.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Nations that participated in the previous games in London 1948 but were absent in Helsinki 1952 included Afghanistan, Colombia, Malta, Peru and Syria.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Puerto Rico is an unincorporated territory and commonwealth of the United States.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Bahamas, Bermuda, Gold Coast (modern-day Ghana), Hong Kong, Jamaica, Nigeria, Singapore, Trinidad and Tobago, and British Guyana was all part of the British Empire.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Netherlands Antilles was a constituent country of the Kingdom of Netherlands.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Soviet Union sent the largest delegation.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1952 Games.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The 50th anniversary of the Helsinki Olympic Games was the main motif for one of the first Finnish euro silver commemorative coins, the €10 silver coin minted in 2002.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The reverse depicts part of the Helsinki Olympic Stadium, as well as a section of the 1952 500 markka coin.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The obverse has lettering SUOMI FINLAND 10 EURO, a flame, and Finland is the only country highlighted on Earth.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] In total 2,394,099 admission tickets were printed for the Helsinki games.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] About two million of them were made Bank of Finland banknote printing works.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] To prevent counterfeiting, tickets were printed on watermark banknote paper.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Printing began in July 1951 and lasted four months.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] In early 1952, the race organizers opened their own ticket offices for sales at home and abroad.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Half of the more than two million admission tickets were put up for sale abroad.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] However, only about 250,000 tickets were sold.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] However, foreign tourists also bought a lot of tickets from Finland.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] A total of 1,376,512 tickets were sold for various competition events.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] There were four different price categories.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Prices varied between 300 and 2,100 FIM, which in current currency corresponds to about 9–65 euros.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Ticket revenue totaled approximately FIM 965 million, or EUR 29.7 million.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Entrance tickets were printed in ten different colors, depending on the venue and the auditorium.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Except for the color, the flags were all similar in appearance.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The texts in Finnish, Swedish, English and French were printed on them, and the sport was also indicated by a symbol in the upper left corner.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] A spectator map was printed on the back of the entrance tickets.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Tickets sold to Finland only marked their Price Category, foreign tickets also marked the price US Dollars.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] In addition to tickets made by the organizers, the City of Hämeenlinna printed its own entry tickets for modern pentathlon competitions held locally.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] They were simpler in design than other tickets.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The Olympics influenced the Finns, the City of Helsinki and the image of foreigners.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The Olympics can even be considered a symbolic decision for the post-war years in Finland.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Reconstruction of the land was practically completed in 1952, although at the beginning of the decade many had lived in temporary housing.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The last war reparations was paid in September 1952, and regulatory policy was abolished at the same time.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] On the closing day of the Games, 3 August 1952, President J.K.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Paasikivi wrote in his diary: "The Olympics were a great success.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Foreigners, including the magazines, have praised the good organization.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Helsinki cityscape was clearly a new impetus for the Olympics.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The development of Helsinki had already begun in the late 1930s, when Parliament House, Lasipalatsi and Pääposti were built.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Olympic dreams motivate many construction projects.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Helsinki's entertainment and nightlife was modest compared to previous race hosts.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Many temporary restaurants and entertainment venues were set up in the city for the Games.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The city had been planning a fair for decades, but even for this project, the Olympic host gave the final impetus.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] After the competition was confirmed, the city of Helsinki started looking for a place for an amusement park in Alppila.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The Linnanmäki Amusement Park was opened on 27 May 1950 on a plot leased in December 1949.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The Olympics also developed Helsinki's infrastructure with the construction of a new airport, Olympic Pier, new asphalt and the city's first traffic lights.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The Olympic spirit was also visible outside the capital region.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] In 1952, Finland's first rest stop for motorists was opened in Lahnajärvi, along the former Highway 1 (current road 110).
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The impact of the Olympics on Finns is difficult to define.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] It was certainly good for Finns' self-confidence to create a successful major event together and at the same time get a new kind of contact with the interaction between peoples.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] For the first time, many Finns were in contact with non-Caucasian foreigners at the Games.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] At the same time, the Olympics united Finns in their disputes.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] For example, Finnish Workers' Sports Federation and Finnish Sports Federation strong disputes between were on a break during the Olympics, even though they continued even after the Games.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] With internationalization, new products also arrived in Finland.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The best known of these is Coca-Cola (Coca-Cola arrived in Finland as early as the 1930s through Stockmann).
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] In addition, chewing gum was imported for the first time, and Alko launched new drinks, including Gin Long Drink.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Finland's relations with United Kingdom clearly warmed up thanks to the Olympics.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] This was particularly influenced by the fact that Prince Philip, who came to visit the Games, received a warm welcome in Finland.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] After the Second World War, Britain had been rude to Finland, but the Olympics showed that Finland belonged to the Western world.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] In Finland, the Helsinki Olympics are sometimes called the last real Olympics, when trying to emphasize the nature of the Games as the last Games of the true Olympic spirit, a sporting and non-commercial event.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] For example, a book about competitions written by Antero Raevuori is named after this saying.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] However, the phrase was invented in Finland and is not used elsewhere in the world.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] It was developed at the turn of the 1970s and 1980s, when doping began to become more widespread in sports, 1972 Summer Olympics the Munich massacre, and the 1976, 1980 and 1984 the Summer Olympics were widely boycotted.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] In a way, the Helsinki Olympics were a return to smaller competitions due to resources, as Finland is the smallest country to host the Summer Olympics.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] However the 1956 Summer Olympics involved fewer participating athletes than in Helsinki, and in practice it was not until the 1970s that the Games clearly began to expand.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The Helsinki Olympics were still relatively non-commercial, although the Polish press, for example, barked at the Helsinki Olympics as "competitions for disgusting traders".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The Helsinki Games were also not much smaller in terms of marketing than the following Games, and marketing was well known in the Olympic world with Kodak supporting the Games as far back as the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an effort that was led by Faisal of Saudi Arabia, the initial countries that OAPEC targeted were Canada, Japan, the Netherlands, the United Kingdom, and the United States.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This list was later expanded to include Portugal, Rhodesia, and South Africa.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In March 1974, OAPEC lifted the embargo, but the price of oil had risen by nearly 300%: from US$3 per barrel ($19/m3) to nearly US$12 per barrel ($75/m3) globally.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Prices in the United States were significantly higher than the global average.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After it was implemented, the embargo caused an oil crisis, or "shock", with many short- and long-term effects on the global economy as well as on global politics.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The 1973 embargo later came to be referred to as the **first oil shock**.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A second oil shock occurred in 1979 in the aftermath of the Iranian Revolution.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Following the Israeli Declaration of Independence in 1948, there has been conflict between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East, including several wars.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Suez Crisis, also known as the Second Arab–Israeli war, was sparked by Israel's southern port of Eilat being blocked by Egypt, which also nationalized the Suez Canal belonging to French and British investors.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As a result of the war, the Suez Canal was closed for several months between 1956 and 1957.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Six-Day War of 1967 included an Israeli invasion of the Egyptian Sinai Peninsula, which resulted in Egypt closing the Suez Canal for eight years.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Following the Yom Kippur War, the canal was cleared in 1974 and opened again in 1975.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OAPEC countries cut production of oil and placed an embargo on oil exports to the United States after Richard Nixon requested $2.2 billion to support Israel's war effort.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nevertheless, the embargo lasted only until January 1974, though the price of oil remained high afterwards.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] By 1969, American domestic production of oil was peaking and could not keep pace with increasing demand from vehicles.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The US was importing 350 million barrels (56 million cubic metres) per year by the late 1950s, mostly from Venezuela and Canada.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because of transportation costs and tariffs, it never purchased much oil from the Middle East.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1973, US production had declined to 16% of global output.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Eisenhower imposed quotas on foreign oil that would stay in place between 1959 and 1973.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Critics called it the "drain America first" policy.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Some scholars believe the policy contributed to the decline of domestic US oil production in the early 1970s.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The cheapness of oil compared with coal led to the decline of the coal industry.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1951, 51% of the United States' energy came from coal, and by 1973, only 19% of American industry was coal-based.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The decline in domestic oil production, combined with the country's increasing reliance on oil as a source of power, made the US economy vulnerable to a foreign oil embargo.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] When Richard Nixon became US president in 1969, he assigned George Shultz to head a committee to review the Eisenhower-era quota program.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Shultz's committee recommended that the quotas be abolished and replaced with tariffs, but Nixon decided to keep the quotas due to vigorous political opposition.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon imposed a price ceiling on oil in August 1971 as demand for oil was increasing and production was declining, which increased dependence on oil imports as consumption was bolstered by low prices.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1973, Nixon announced the end of the quota system.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Between 1970 and 1973 US imports of crude oil had nearly doubled, reaching 6.2 million barrels per day in 1973.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Until 1973, an abundance of oil supply had kept the market price of oil lower than the posted price.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1970, American oil production peaked and the United States began to import more oil.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Oil imports rose by 52% between 1969 and 1972.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] By 1972, 83% of the American oil imports came from the Middle East.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Throughout the 1960s, the price for a barrel of oil remained at $1.80, meaning that with the effects of inflation considered the price of oil in real terms got progressively lower throughout the decade, with Americans paying less for oil in 1969 than they had in 1959.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Even after a price for a barrel of oil rose to $2.00 in 1971, adjusted for inflation, people in the Western nations were paying less for oil in 1971 than they had in 1958.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The extremely low price of oil served as the basis for the "long summer" of prosperity and mass affluence that began in 1945.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), was founded by five oil producing countries at a Baghdad conference on 14 September 1960.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The five founding members of OPEC were Venezuela, Iraq, Saudi Arabia, Iran and Kuwait.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC was organized after the oil companies slashed the posted price of oil, but the posted price of oil remained consistently higher than the market price of oil between 1961 and 1972.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1963, the Seven Sisters controlled 86% of the oil produced by OPEC countries, but by 1970 the rise of "independent oil companies" had decreased their share to 77%.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The entry of three new oil producers—Algeria, Libya and Nigeria—meant that by 1970, 81 oil companies were doing business in the Middle East.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In the early 1960s Libya, Indonesia and Qatar joined OPEC.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC was generally regarded as ineffective until political turbulence in Libya and Iraq strengthened their position in 1970.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Additionally, increasing Soviet influence provided oil producing countries with alternative means of transporting oil to markets.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Under the Tehran Price Agreement of 1971, signed on 14 February, the posted price of oil was increased and, due to a decline in the value of the US dollar relative to gold, certain anti-inflationary measures were enacted.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A severe drain on US gold reserves lead to higher inflation and lack of confidence in the strength of the dollar, President Nixon issued Executive Order 11615 on August 15, 1971, which closed the gold window.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This action made the dollar inconvertible to gold directly, except on the open market, and was soon dubbed the *Nixon Shock*, leading eventually to the collapse of the Bretton Woods system in 1976.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because oil was priced in dollars, oil producers' real income decreased when the dollar started to float free of the old link to gold.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In September 1971, OPEC issued a joint communiqué stating that from then on, they would price oil in terms of a fixed amount of gold.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After 1971, OPEC was slow to readjust prices to reflect this depreciation.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] From 1947 to 1967, the dollar price of oil had risen by less than two percent per year.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Until the oil shock, the price had also remained fairly stable versus other currencies and commodities.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC ministers had not developed institutional mechanisms to update prices in sync with changing market conditions, so their real incomes lagged.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The substantial price increases of 1973–1974 largely returned their prices and corresponding incomes to former levels in terms of commodities such as gold.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Arab oil producing countries had attempted to use oil as leverage to influence political events on two prior occasions—the first was the Suez Crisis in 1956 when the United Kingdom, France and Israel invaded Egypt.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During the conflict the Syrians sabotaged both the Trans-Arabian Pipeline and the Iraq–Baniyas pipeline, which disrupted the supply of oil to Western Europe.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The second instance was when war broke out between Egypt and Israel in 1967, but despite continued Egyptian and Syrian enmity against Israel, the embargo lasted only a few months.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Most scholars agree that the 1967 embargo was ineffective.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Although some members of the Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting Countries (OAPEC) supported the use of oil as a weapon to influence the political outcome of the Arab–Israeli conflict, Saudi Arabia had traditionally been the strongest supporter of separating oil from politics.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Saudis were wary of the tactic due to the availability of oil from non-Arab oil producing countries, and in the decades leading up to the crisis, the region's conservative monarchies had grown dependent on Western support to ensure their continued survival as Nasserism gained traction.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On the other hand, Algeria, Iraq and Libya had strongly supported the use of oil as a weapon in the conflict.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Arab newspapers like the Egyptian *Al-Ahram*, Lebanese *An-Nahar* and Iraqi *Al-Thawra* had historically been supportive of the use of oil as a weapon.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1970, President Nasser of Egypt died and was succeeded by Anwar Sadat, a man who believed in the diplomacy of surprise, in engaging in sudden moves to upset the diplomatic equilibrium.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Sadat liked to say that his favourite game was backgammon, a game where skill and persistence was rewarded, but was best won by sudden gambles, making an analogy between how he played backgammon and conducted his diplomacy.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Under Nasser, Egypt and Saudi Arabia had engaged what was known as the Arab Cold War, but Sadat got along very well with King Faisal of Saudi Arabia, forming an alliance between the most populous Arab state and the wealthiest Arab state.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Unlike the secularist Nasser, Sadat was a pious Muslim and he had a strong personal rapport with King Faisal, who was an equally pious Muslim.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The man largely in charge of American foreign policy, the National Security Adviser, Henry Kissinger, later admitted that he was so engrossed with the Paris peace talks to end the Vietnam war that he and others in Washington missed the significance of the Egyptian-Saudi alliance.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the same time that Sadat moved closer to Saudi Arabia, he also wanted a rapprochement with the United States and to move Egypt away from its alliance with the Soviet Union.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1971, the US had information that the Arab states were willing to implement another embargo.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In July 1972, Sadat expelled all 16,000 of the Soviet military personnel in Egypt in a signal that he wanted better relations with the United States.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger was taken completely by surprise by Sadat's move, saying: "Why has he done me this favor?
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] For Sadat, cost was no object as the money to buy Soviet arms came from Saudi Arabia.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the same time, Faisal promised Sadat that if it should come to war, Saudi Arabia would embargo oil to the West.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In April 1973, the Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani visited Washington to meet Kissinger and told him that King Faisal was becoming more and more unhappy with the United States, saying he wanted America to pressure Israel to return all the lands captured in the Six Day War of 1967.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In a later interview, Yamani accused Kissinger of not taking his warning seriously, saying all he did was to ask him not to speak anymore of this threat.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Angry at Kissinger, Yamani, in an interview with the *Washington Post* on April 19, 1973, warned that King Faisal was considering an oil embargo.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the time, the general feeling in Washington was the Saudis were bluffing and nothing would come of their threat to impose an oil embargo.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The fact that Faisal's ineffectual half brother King Saud had imposed a crippling oil embargo on Britain and France during the Suez War of 1956 was not considered an important precedent.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The CEOs of four of the United States' oil companies, after speaking with Faisal, arrived in Washington in May 1973 with the warning that Faisal was considerably tougher, more intelligent and more ruthless than his half-brother Saud whom he had deposed in 1964, and that his threats were serious.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger declined to meet the four CEOs.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an assessment done by Kissinger and his staff about the Middle East in the summer of 1973, the repeated statements by Sadat about waging *jihad* against Israel were dismissed as empty talk, while the warnings from King Faisal were likewise regarded as inconsequential.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In September 1973, Nixon fired Rogers as Secretary of State and replaced him with Kissinger.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger later stated he had not been given enough time to know the Middle East, as he settled into the State Department's office at Foggy Bottom as Egypt and Syria attacked Israel on 6 October 1973.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 6 October 1973, the Yom Kippur began when Egypt attacked the Bar Lev Line in the Sinai Peninsula and Syria launched an offensive in the Golan Heights, both of which had been occupied by Israel during the 1967 Six-Day War.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal of Saudi Arabia was supportive, and on 8 October 1973, he told two Egyptian envoys: "You have made us all proud.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In the past we could not lift our heads up.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] He promised to give to Egypt a quality of aid worth $200 million US dollars to assist with the war effort, and stated he was willing to use the "oil weapon" if necessary to support Egypt.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The war began during the height of the Watergate scandal; as such Nixon largely let Kissinger manage foreign policy as he, Nixon, was distracted by the scandal.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger promised Israeli Prime Minister Golda Meir that the United States would replace its losses in equipment after the war.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon had ordered an arms lift to Israel on 12 October 1973, but Kissinger used the excuse of bureaucratic delays to limit the amount of weapons and ammunition sent to Israel.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Arab concept of the "peace of the brave", i.e. a victorious leader being magnanimous to his defeated opponents, meant there was a possibility that Sadat at least would make peace with Israel provided that the war ended in such a way that Egypt was not perceived to be defeated.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Likewise, Kissinger regarded Meir as being rather arrogant and believed that an armistice that ended the war in a manner that was not an unambiguous Israeli victory would make her more humble.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As both Syria and Egypt lost much equipment during the fighting, the Soviet Union began to fly new equipment in, starting on 12 October.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Soviet flights to Syria and Egypt were recorded by the British radar stations in Cyprus.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Though the Soviets were flying in an average of 60 flights per day, exaggerated accounts appeared in Western newspapers speaking of "one hundred flights per day".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At this point, both Nixon and Kissinger began to see the October War more in terms of the Cold War rather than Middle Eastern politics, both seeing the Soviet arms lifts to Egypt and Syria as a Soviet power play that required an American answer.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On October 12, 1973, US president Richard Nixon authorized Operation Nickel Grass, a strategic airlift to deliver weapons and supplies to Israel in order to replace its materiel losses.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The first American weapons to Israel arrived on 15 October 1973, and despite Nixon's orders the number of American planes flying into Tel Aviv were initially limited.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After the first week of the war, the Israelis had halted the Syrian offensive in the Golan Heights and were pushing back the Syrians back towards Damascus.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Along the Suez canal, however, there was heavy fighting, with the Egyptians holding their own.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At an OPEC summit at the Sheraton Hotel in Kuwait City on 16 October 1973, it was announced the price of oil would go from $3.01 US dollars per barrel to $5.12 per barrel.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The news about the war on 16 October was grim from the Arab viewpoint, with the Syrians steadily being pushed back, while Israelis had opened a counter-offensive against the Egyptians and crossed the Great Bitter Lake.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Responses from stated representatives at the meeting were varied.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani stated, in a 1981 interview, that "[t]he king still wanted to give America a chance to stay out of the fighting.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] So we agreed to cut back production by just 5 percent per month.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A full embargo, we agreed, was something we would implement only if we felt that things were absolutely hopeless".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Iranian delegation left the summit after agreeing to the price increase, as the Shah of Iran only supported higher oil prices.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Oil Minister of Iraq, Sa'dun Hammadi demanded the "total nationalization" of all assets of American oil companies in the Middle East, the withdrawal of all Arab funds from the United States and for all Arab states to break diplomatic relations with the United States.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Libyan Oil Minister, Izz al-Din al-Mabruk, called for the nationalization of all the assets of all Western oil companies in the Middle East.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Saudi delegation led by Yemani, supported by the Algerian delegation, fought hard against the Iraqi and Libyan demands for an embargo, as Yemani maintained that forcing through an increase in the price of oil was the best way to influence the United States.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Hammadi and the rest of the Iraqi delegation left upset as Yemani had won over the majority of the delegations to the Saudi viewpoint.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The statement issued after midnight at the Sheraton Hotel was handwritten and, reflecting the tense talk, had several paragraphs crossed out while other paragraphs were written in by different hands.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 17 October, Arab oil producers cut production by 5% and threatened an oil embargo against Israel's wartime allies: the United States, the Netherlands, Rhodesia, South Africa, and Portugal.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 17–19 October 1973, the Saudi Foreign Minister, Omar Al Saqqaf, visited Washington together with the foreign ministers of Algeria, Kuwait and Morocco to warn that there was a real possibility of an oil embargo being imposed.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon promised him that the United States would mediate a settlement to the war that would be "peaceful, just and honorable" to both sides.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] He had ended the Vietnam war on what he felt was an honorable basis and now intended to end the October war in the same manner.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saqqaf complained to King Faisal that Nixon seemed more interested in a dispute about "a burglary" (i.e. the Watergate scandal) than about the war.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During a press conference, an American reporter mocked the threat of an embargo, contemptuously saying the Saudis "could drink their oil", leading Saqqaf to reply in anger "All right, we will!".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Israel took heavy losses in men and materiel during the fighting against Egypt and Syria, and on 18 October 1973, Meir requested $850 million worth of American arms and equipment to replace its materiel losses.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon decided, characteristically, to act on an epic scale; Instead of the $850 million worth of arms requested, he sent a request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms to Israel, which was promptly approved.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon, whose administration was being badly battered by the Watergate scandal, felt that a bold foreign policy move might resuscitate his administration.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an interview with the British historian Robert Lacey in 1981, Kissinger later admitted about the arms lift to Israel: "I made a mistake.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In retrospect it was not the best considered decision we made".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The arms lift enraged King Faisal of Saudi Arabia.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was angry that Israel had only asked for $850 million worth of American weapons, and instead received an unsolicited $2.2 billion worth of weapons, which he perceived as a sign of the pro-Israeli slant of American foreign policy.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal also felt insulted that Nixon had just promised Saqqaf an "honorable" peace the day before he submitted the request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms for Israel, which he saw as an act of duplicity on Nixon's part.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal had been opposed to a total embargo and only agreed to the 5% cut on 17 October under pressure from other Arab states.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal felt his efforts on behalf the United States were not being appreciated in Washington, which increased his fury at Nixon.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On the afternoon of 19 October 1973, Faisal was in his office when he learned about the United States sending $2.2 billion worth of weapons to Israel, and discussed the issue with two of his closest advisers, Abdullah ibn Abdul Rahman and Rashad Pharaon.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The king called Yamani at about 8 pm, and told him he was needed at the Riyassa Palace immediately.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Yamani told the king: "The TV news goes out at nine.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] If you make a decision now, we can get it announced at once".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The king replied "Write this down" and announced he was placing a total embargo on the United States.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Most of the other oil-producing Arab states joined the embargo.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Algeria, Iraq, and Libya promoted the embargo, but did not actively enforce it.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo was accompanied by gradual monthly production cuts—by December, production had been cut to 25% of September levels.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This contributed to a global recession and increased tension between the United States and several of its European allies, who faulted the US for provoking an embargo by providing what many viewed as unconditional assistance to Israel.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OAPEC demanded a complete Israeli withdrawal from all territories beyond the 1949 Armistice border.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo lasted from October 1973 to March 1974.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because every Arab state except for Iraq and Libya joined the oil embargo, oil exports from the Middle East to the West were down by 60–70% by November 1973.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Japan and the nations of western Europe imported some 75% of their oil from the Near East.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo led to immediate and sharp price raises, as Lacey noted that "competing desperately for dwindling supplies, consumers showed themselves willing to pay unparalleled money for their oil".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil reserves.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo imposed on the United States led to shortages of oil in the United States, which set an inflationary spiral, as the new high prices for oil in the American market led to sharp increases of the price of oil in nations not subjected to the embargo.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] When the Iranian state oil company held an auction on 16 December 1973, bids for some $17 US dollars per barrel of oil were made.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In late December 1973, OPEC held a conference in Vienna when it was announced the price for a barrel of oil was to increase from $5 US dollars per barrel to $11.65 US dollars per barrel.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was opposed to the price increase, which was largely the work of the Iranian delegation.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 22 February 1974, King Faisal chaired the second summit of Islamic states in Lahore, which, unlike the first summit that Faisal had chaired in 1969, was not boycotted by Iraq and Syria.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was acclaimed as a conquering hero who humiliated and humbled the West by wrecking its economy.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The prime minister of Pakistan, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, opened the conference by stating: "The armies of Pakistan are the armies of Islam.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On November 7, 1973, Kissinger flew to Riyadh to meet King Faisal and ask him to end the oil embargo in exchange for promising to be "evenhanded" with the Arab-Israeli dispute.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As the plane carrying him prepared to land in Riyadh, Kissinger was clearly nervous at the prospect of negotiating with the stern Wahhabi Faisal who had a marked dislike of Jews.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During a summit in Cairo the day before, Kissinger asked Sadat what Faisal was like and was told: "Well, Dr.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Henry, he will probably go on with you about Communism and the Jews".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] King Faisal's two great hatreds were communism and Zionism, as he believed that the Soviet Union and Israel were plotting together against Islam.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Initially, Secretary of Defense James Schlesinger suggested to Kissinger that the USA invade Saudi Arabia and another Arab countries and seize their oil fields.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger stated in a private state department meeting that it's “ridiculous that the civilized world is held up by 8 million savages...
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Can’t we overthrow one of the sheikhs just to show that we can do it?” They formed a plan to invade Abu Dhabi, Kuwait, and Saudi Arabia.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger publicly threatened "countermeasures" in a November 21, 1973 press conference if the embargo was not lifted, and the Saudis responded with threatening further oil cuts and to burn their oil fields if the US military invaded.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After the CIA confirmed these threats, Kissinger gave up military intervention and decided to deal with Israel's troop withdrawals, settling on diplomatic solutions to the oil embargo.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 18 March 1974, King Faisal ended the oil embargo.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Sadat had reported to Faisal that the United States was being more "evenhanded", and Kissinger had promised to sell Saudi Arabia weapons that it had previously denied under the grounds that they might be used against Israel.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Since Israeli forces did not withdraw to the 1949 Armistice Line, the majority of scholars believe that the embargo was a failure.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Roy Licklieder, in his 1988 book *Political Power and the Arab Oil Weapon*, concluded that the embargo was a failure because the countries that were targeted by the embargo did not change their policies on the Arab–Israeli conflict.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Licklieder believed that any long term changes were caused by the OPEC increase in the posted price of oil, and not the OAPEC embargo.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Daniel Yergin, on the other hand, has said that the embargo "remade the international economy".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Over the long term, the oil embargo changed the nature of policy in the West towards increased exploration, alternative energy research, energy conservation and more restrictive monetary policy to better fight inflation.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] For further details see the "Energy crisis" series by Facts on File.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The effects of the embargo were immediate.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC forced oil companies to increase payments drastically.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The price of oil quadrupled by 1974 from US$3 to nearly US$12 per 42 gallon barrel ($75 per cubic meter), equivalent in 2018 dollars to a price rise from $17 to $61 per barrel.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil, but only 4% of the oil used in the United States in 1973 came from the kingdom.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] However, Saudi Arabia plays an over-sized role within the Arab world.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1973, about 25% of the oil used in the United States came from Arab countries.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The shortage of oil within the United States caused by the Arab oil embargo forced prices to rise, which led price rises globally.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Oil producers that had not joined the embargo such as Iran, Venezuela, Libya and Iraq demanded higher prices in Japan and Europe, as an initiative to ship oil to those places instead of the United States, setting off a worldwide inflationary spiral.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Although the embargo did not severely disrupt US oil supplies—since Americans imported more oil from non-embargoed nations such as Iran—the resulting 400% increase in oil prices caused by the embargo damaged the American economy.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A number of nations such as Venezuela, Nigeria, Iran and Iraq increased their oil production during the embargo, and sold their oil at a higher price.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The leader who pushed the most for higher oil prices was the Shah of Iran, and the Italian historian Giuliano Garavini has argued that the leader most responsible for the West's economic problems during the "oil shock" was not King Faisal, but rather the Shah.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Some of the nations that were classified as "friendly" to the Arab viewpoint in regards to the Arab-Israeli dispute such as France and Belgium were the ones who suffered the most from the worldwide inflation caused by the embargo.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In March 1974, the crisis eased when the embargo was lifted after negotiations at the Washington Oil Summit, but the effects lingered throughout the 1970s.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The dollar price of energy increased again in 1975, amid the weakening competitive position of the dollar in world markets.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Arab oil embargo ended the long period of prosperity in the West that had begun in 1945, throwing the world's economy into the steepest economic contraction since the Great Depression.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The "long summer" of prosperity in the post-war years had made possible the "swinging sixties" and the related rise of a rebellious youth culture, as it was easy to be hedonist or in rebellion against traditional values in a time of unprecedented prosperity.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] 1945 to 1973 had been a period of unprecedented prosperity in the West, a "long summer" that many believed would never end.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Its abrupt end in 1973, as the oil embargo increased the price of oil by 400% within a matter of days and threw the world's economy into a sharp recession, with unemployment mounting and inflation raging, came as a profound shock.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The end of what the French called the *Trente Glorieuses* ("Glorious Thirty" [years]) led to widespread pessimism in the West, with the *Financial Times* running a famous headline in late 1973 saying, "The Future will be subject to Delay".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In an August 1974 address to the General Assembly, Kurt Waldheim, the secretary-general of the United Nations, complained about "the note of helplessness and fatalism creeping into world affairs".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The sudden and abrupt end of the "long summer" of prosperity in 1973-1974 played a major role in the pessimistic mood that characterized the culture of the West of the 1970s.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1975, a report to Congress from the Federal Energy Administration estimated that the embargo of 1973–1974 had caused about 500,000 Americans to lose their jobs, and caused a GNP loss between $10 billion–$20 billion.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] This price increase had a dramatic effect on oil exporting nations, for the countries of the Middle East who had long been dominated by the industrial powers were seen to have taken control of a vital commodity.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil-exporting nations began to accumulate vast wealth.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Some of the income was dispensed in the form of aid to other underdeveloped nations whose economies had been caught between higher oil prices and lower prices for their own export commodities, amid shrinking Western demand.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Much went for arms purchases that exacerbated political tensions, particularly in the Middle East.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The 400% increase in the world oil prices led to extravagant promises being made by the leaders of oil-producing nations.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Shah of Iran told his subjects in a speech in December 1973 that he was launching "Great Civilization" project that would make Iran into a First World nation by the 1990s.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] President Carlos Andrés Pérez of Venezuela likewise launched his *Le Gran Venezuela* project intended to make Venezuela into a First World nation.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] President Yakubu Gowon of Nigeria told his people that henceforward Nigeria's main problem would be "managing abundance".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] After the oil shock, Nigeria presented itself as the first African nation that would reach First World status.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In Lagos, a series of stately modernist buildings were erected as appropriate for a nation that saw itself as the leader of all Black Africa.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Much of the oil wealth in Nigeria was stolen by corrupt politicians.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] At least some of Nigeria's new oil wealth went to rebuild the areas devastated by the civil war of 1967-1970 and to address the complaints that too much of Nigeria's oil wealth went to the federal government in Lagos instead of the people.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The new wealth generated by the "oil shock" allowed for Chairman Houari Boumédiène of Algeria to become a global leader, courted by elites in the First World and the Third World.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil embargo led a sudden interest in the Palestinian issue.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Between 1973 and 1981, Saudi Arabia donated a sum worth $1 billion US dollars to the Palestine Liberation Organization, which thus had a budget that exceeded that of many Third World nations.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On November 8, 1973, Kissinger became the first Secretary of State to meet with a Saudi leader since 1953, as he met King Faisal to ask him to end the embargo.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Within two week of the embargo being launched, all of the foreign ministers of the nations of the European Economic Community, now the European Union, met in a conference to issue a statement calling for Israel "to end the territorial occupation which has maintained since the conflict of 1967".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On December 11, 1973, the Japanese Foreign Minister Masayoshi Ōhira flew in to Riyadh to meet King Faisal for "talks on improving bilateral relations".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Shortly afterwards, the French foreign minister Michel Jobert arrived to sign an agreement that provided oil for France for the next twenty years.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On January 24, 1974, as the Shah of Iran, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, was coming off the ski slopes of St.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Moritz, he was met by the British Chancellor of Exchequer, Anthony Barber, and the Trade Secretary, Peter Walker.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In a role-reversal, Barber and Walker paid homage to the Shah, who promised them that his nation would sell the United Kingdom 5 million tons of oil in exchange for some £100 million of British goods, to aid his plans to industrialize Iran.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia experienced an upsurge of prosperity and affluence after the oil embargo, whose consequences horrified King Faisal.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faisal, who was devoted to a harsh puritanical strain of Sunni Islam known in the West as Wahhabism, was appalled by the way that his subjects became materialistic, devoted only to conspicuous consumption and greed as they lost interest in Islam.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Lacey wrote: "The spiritual dangers of easy affluence distressed him more.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] His simple gesture of piety and honor seemed to have opened a Pandora's Box that threatened to turn his realm into a parody of all he held dear".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the last two of years of his life, Faisal fell into depression over the way his subjects had been seduced into a consumerist lifestyle, becoming lost in a sense of "melancholia".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faisal's son, Crown Prince Mohammad told Lacey in 1981: "The profligacy, the greed, he felt he could not stem it.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] He become so bound up in his work, there was almost nothing private of him left".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A sign of the changed values was that despite the total ban on alcohol in Saudi Arabia, drinking and drug use became common with the younger members of the House of Saud.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] James Akins, the American ambassador in Riyadh reported; "the sky over Riyadh is black with vultures with new get-richer-quicker plans under their wings".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1974, property prices in Riyadh doubled on a weekly basis for the entire year, as the prosperity led to a real estate speculation bubble that was often compared to the Klondike gold rush of 1898–1899.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] At the Red Sea port of Jeddah, there were so many ships queuing up laden with cement for the construction boom in Saudi Arabia, that construction contractors hired helicopters to fly the cement in, twenty bags per flight.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A number of families engaged in the Saudi construction industry such as the Juffali, Alireza, al-Khasshoggi and the bin Laden families all became very wealthy as a result of the construction boom.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The period after the oil shock of 1973–1974 is still fondly remembered in Saudi Arabia as the "age of abundance", where nearly everyone had a significant increase in their standard of living.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The wealth and corruption generated by the oil shock led to a fundamentalist backlash in Saudi Arabia.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On 20 November 1979, Islam's holiest shrine, the Grand Mosque of Mecca, was seized by a group who proclaimed themselves to be the followers of the Mahdi, a messianic figure said to appear at the dawn of every Muslim century to strike down the enemies of Islam.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The leader of the uprising, Juhayman al-Otaybi, read out a list of grievances, as he accused the House of Saud of being corrupt and degenerate, listing by name a number of Saudi princes who were engaged in dubious business dealings and/or who drank alcohol.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Saudi Army recaptured the Grand Mosque, and the surviving "renegades", as the rebels were labelled, were executed.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In Algeria, the "oil shock" led to the establishment of a welfare state where none had existed previously.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The lower oil prices of the 1980s along with cutbacks and the belief that the FLN regime was corrupt helped cause the riots of October 1988 against the FLN regime, that killed at least 500 people.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The riots were largely caused by the fact that the low oil prices had forced the Algerian state to end many of its more generous social policies between 1986 and 1988, leading to an unemployment rate of 30% by 1988, along with the knowledge that the FLN regime had stolen millions.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the aftermath of the October riots, President Chadli Bendjedid began a transition to democracy.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The first free elections in Algeria in January 1992 were won by the Islamist FIS, which led to a military coup and an outbreak of a civil war that killed hundreds of thousands of Algerians.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC-member states raised the prospect of nationalization of oil company holdings.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Most notably, Saudi Arabia nationalized Aramco in 1980 under the leadership of Saudi oil minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] As other OPEC nations followed suit, the cartel's income soared.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia undertook a series of ambitious five-year development plans.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The biggest began in 1980, funded at $250 billion.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Other cartel members also undertook major economic development programs.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Control of oil became known as the "oil weapon".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It came in the form of an embargo and production cutbacks from the Arab states.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The weapon was aimed at the United States, Great Britain, Canada, Japan and the Netherlands.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] These target governments perceived that the intent was to push them towards a more pro-Arab position.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] However, the affected countries did not undertake dramatic policy changes.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The risk that the Middle East could become another superpower confrontation with the USSR was of more concern to Washington than oil.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Further, interest groups and government agencies more worried about energy were no match for Kissinger's dominance.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo had a negative influence on the US economy, causing immediate demands to address the threats to US energy security.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On an international level, the price increases changed competitive positions in many industries, such as automobiles.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Macroeconomic problems consisted of both inflationary and deflationary impacts.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo left oil companies searching for new ways to increase oil supplies, even in rugged terrain such as the Arctic.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Finding oil and developing new fields usually required five to 10 years before significant production.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The average US retail price of a gallon of regular gasoline rose 43% from 38.5¢ in May 1973 to 55.1¢ in June 1974.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] State governments asked citizens not to put up Christmas lights.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Oregon banned Christmas and commercial lighting altogether.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Politicians called for a national gasoline rationing program.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Nixon asked gasoline retailers to voluntarily not sell gasoline on Saturday nights or Sundays.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] 90% of gas station owners complied, which produced long lines of motorists wanting to fill up their cars while they still could.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The "oil shock" provided considerable impetus to the American nuclear industry as a way to achieve "energy independence" from the Middle East.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On 7 November 1973, Nixon in an address to Congress called for Project Independence to make the United States self-sufficient in energy by 1980, which called for a massive investment in the nuclear industry.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Nixon envisioned nuclear energy as more economical, and was encouraged by the enthusiasm of many officials who saw nuclear energy as the technology of the future.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the late 1960s, a lively environmentalist movement had emerged in the United States, and the Project Independence nuclear program was the subject of much debate in both the media and Congress.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The ensuing debates revealed that many of the claims made for nuclear power underestimated the true costs of nuclear reactors.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Equally problematic was where to safety store the spent nuclear rods that emitted a toxic level of radioactivity for centuries afterward, in a cost-effective manner.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The issue of the spent nuclear rods was especially difficult because of NIMBYism, where communities proved unwilling to accept a storage place for the inevitable by-product of nuclear power, the spent nuclear rods, with the demand that the government find some other community to store the rods.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Many of the nuclear reactors ordered in 1973 were cancelled due to cost overruns, while over 100 nuclear plants were shut down as uneconomical over the next 10 years.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Unlike nations that tried to use nuclear power as a way for energy independence such as France and Sweden, the United States had substantial reserves of its own oil, which weakened the case for nuclear power in the ensuring debates.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By 1989, only 18% of American energy came from nuclear power plants, which was a fraction of what Project Independence had envisioned in 1973.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil shock led to anti-Arab feelings becoming common.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Cartoons published in American newspapers during the oil shock depicted Arabs as disgusting, ugly, obese, corrupt and greedy.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the cartoons, the long hooked Semitic noses that had traditionally been featured in anti-Jewish cartoons were applied to the Arab sheiks as a way to illustrate their supposed greed.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] American public opinion did not see the use of the "oil weapon" as due to politics, and tended to explain the embargo as only due to the excessive greed of King Faisal and the other Arab leaders, hence the use of the hooked Semitic nose in the cartoons as a sort of shorthand for insatiable greed.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Soviet Union was not a beneficiary of the oil crisis.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis prompted the USSR to raise energy prices within the Council on Mutual Economic Assistance (CMEA).
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo was not uniform across Western Europe.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Of the nine members of the European Economic Community (EEC), the Netherlands faced a complete embargo.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By contrast Britain and France received almost uninterrupted supplies.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] That was their reward for refusing to allow the US to use their airfields and stopping arms and supplies to both the Arabs and the Israelis.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The other six EEC nations faced partial cutbacks.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The UK had traditionally been an ally of Israel, and Harold Wilson's government supported the Israelis during the Six-Day War.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] His successor, Ted Heath, reversed this policy in 1970, calling for Israel to withdraw to its pre-1967 borders.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The devalued franc made imports more expensive for French consumers, which encouraged them to buy French products, while making French products cheaper abroad.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] France was entirely dependent upon imported oil, through French companies continued to lease the oil concessions in Algeria until 1971.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The low price of oil internationally compensated to a certain extent for the higher price of oil caused by the devaluation.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The devalued franc ensured that the dramatic price increases caused by the oil shock hit the French economy especially hard in 1973.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The UK, Germany, Italy, Switzerland and Norway banned flying, driving and boating on Sundays.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Sweden rationed gasoline and heating oil.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Netherlands imposed prison sentences for those who used more than their ration of electricity.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The EEC was unable to achieve a common policy during the first month of the embargo.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It issued a statement on November 6, after the embargo and price rises had begun.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It was widely viewed as pro-Arab, supporting the Franco-British line on the war.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC duly lifted its embargo from all EEC members.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The other European states did not rally in defense of the Dutch who were left to fend for themselves and instead reached bilateral deals with Saudi Arabia, Iraq and Iran.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faced with a recession, there was a tendency within the EEC nations to turn inwards away from European integration.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The price rises had a much greater impact in Europe than the embargo.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis retarded the movement towards European economic integration which had been gathering pace ever since the EEC, now the European Union, had been founded in 1957.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1973, the German historian Jens-Uwe Wunderlich wrote that attempts to finish off the European common market came to a "complete standstill" in 1973 and it was not until 1977 that movement towards creating the common market resumed.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In particular, the oil shock increased the appeal of nuclear energy as a way to achieve energy independence from the turbulent Middle East.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Starting in March 1974 with the "Energy Plan" introduced by the premier Pierre Messmer, the French state made a massive investment in nuclear energy.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the 1990s, 80% of all of France's energy came from nuclear plants.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The North Sea oil fields, which were discovered in 1969, did not start to be exploited until 1975, making the United Kingdom entirely dependent upon imported oil in 1973.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The way that world oil prices quadrupled in late 1973 had a very adverse impact on the British economy,.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In a series of speeches in December 1973, the Prime Minister Edward Heath warned that because of the oil shock that the British economy was going into recession and the British people should expect economic austerity.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Heath offered the coal miners a 7% wage increase, which was rejected as insufficient by the miners who went on strike.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Through not subjected to the embargo, the UK faced an energy crisis of its own—a series of strikes by coal miners and railroad workers over the winter of 1973–74 became a major factor in the defeat of Heath's Conservative government in the February 1974 general elections.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The new Labour government told the British to heat only one room in their houses over the winter.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Labour government of Harold Wilson settled the strike by giving the coal miners a 35% pay increase.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japan was hard hit, since it imported 90% of its oil from the Middle East.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It had a stockpile good for 55 days, and another 20-day supply was en route.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Facing its most serious crisis since 1945, the government ordered a 10% cut in the consumption of industrial oil and electricity.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1973, it ordered an immediate 20% cut in oil use and electric power to Japan's major industries, and cutbacks in leisure automobile usage.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Economist predicted the growth rate would plunge from 5% annually, down to zero or even negative territory.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Seeking to take advantage of the crisis, Japanese business called on the government to relax its controls on air pollution and water pollution.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Moscow tried to take advantage by promising energy assistance if Japan renounced its claim to the Kurile Islands.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Instead it made $3.3 billion of dollars in loans to the Arab states and called on Israel to step back.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japan's defensive strategy was explained to Kissinger when he met with top leaders in Tokyo in November 1973.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the long run Japan never wavered in its determination to maintain very strong close ties to the United States, while in self-defense briefly providing the Arab powers with the rhetoric they demanded in return for resuming oil shipments in early 1974.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] To assure future oil flows, Japan added suppliers outside of the Middle East, invested in nuclear power, imposed conservation measures, and provided funding for Arab governments and the Palestinians.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis was a major factor in the long-run shift of Japan's economy away from oil-intensive industries.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japanese auto makers benefited from the crisis.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The jump in gasoline prices helped their small, fuel-efficient models to gain market share from the "gas-guzzling" Detroit competition.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] This triggered a drop in US sales of American cars that lasted into the 1980s.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil crisis contributed to the poor state of the Indian economy and played a role in Indira Gandhi's decision to impose The Emergency, a dictatorship.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The state led a push for coal as an energy source, even though there were reservations about its adverse environmental effects.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil shock destroyed the economy of South Vietnam.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A spokesman for President Nguyễn Văn Thiệu admitted in a TV interview that the government was being "overwhelmed" by the inflation caused by the oil shock.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] An American businessman living in Saigon stated after the oil shock, that attempting to make money in South Vietnam was "like making love to a corpse".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1973, Vietcong sappers attacked and destroyed the petroleum depot of Nha Be, further depleting fuel sources.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the summer of 1974, the US embassy in Saigon reported that morale in the ARVN (Army of the Republic of Vietnam) had fallen to dangerously low levels and it was uncertain how much more longer South Vietnam would last.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] As inflation eroded the value of the South Vietnamese *đồng*, it became common by the summer of 1974 to see ARVN soldiers and their families begging in the streets for food.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1974, the North Vietnamese PAVN (People's Army of Vietnam) launched an offensive in the Central Highlands that was far more successful than expected, due to the ARVN's low morale and weak resistance.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On March 1, 1975, the PAVN launched a major offensive that quickly overran the Central Highlands.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Following their victory in the Central Highlands, the North Vietnamese launched the "Ho Chi Minh Campaign" that captured Saigon on April 30, 1975.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Three of the nations targeted by the embargo were located in southern Africa or had colonies there.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Portugal which ruled the colonies of Angola, Portuguese Guiana (modern Guinea-Bissau), and Portuguese East Africa (modern Mozambique) had fighting colonial wars in all of its African colonies since the 1960s with Angola being the first to rise up in 1961.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Angola is rich in oil, which protected Portugal from the worse of the embargo.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] But the economic stability of the *Estado Novo* regime was damaged by the worldwide inflation, which help cause the Carnation Revolution which toppled the *Estado Novo* regime in April 1974 and led to the restoration of democracy.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Portugal granted independence to all of its colonies except for Macau in 1975.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The British historian Rob Skinner wrote the embargo had a "significant impact" on the South African economy.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The inflationary rise in commodity prices increased the input costs of South African manufacturing, making South African manufactured goods uncompetitive on the world market.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The rise in the price of gold as a hedge against inflation (South Africa has the world's largest gold mines) caused the *rand* to increase in value, which caused further problems for South African manufacturing.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The strategy pursued by the National Party government since 1948 of sponsoring the industrialization of South Africa was derailed by the oil shock, with what Skinner described as "important social and political consequences" for the *apartheid* regime.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Soweto uprising of 1976 was at least in part caused by anger at the high unemployment rate in the black South African community.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Even worse hit than South Africa was Rhodesia (modern Zimbabwe), where oil was already expensive as the white supremacist government of Rhodesia had been under United Nations sanctions since 1965, and thus the smugglers who sold Rhodesia oil charged a premium for their services.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The premium charged by the "sanctions busters" such as Iran increased after the embargo, which threw the Rhodesian economy into recession.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Despite the United Nations sanctions, Rhodesia was a major exporter of chrome, steel and tobacco with the United States exempting "strategical" Rhodesian products such as chrome from the sanctions.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The global recession of 1973–1975 proved more effective than the United Nations in ending the global demand for Rhodesian products, which made the Rhodesian recession especially severe.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Unlike South Africa, which had a sizable and long-standing white population, the white population of Rhodesia was much smaller and more recent.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Rhodesia depended considerably more than South Africa on white immigration to provide enough soldiers for its army, while most of the Rhodesian whites had only arrived in the 1950s and did not have very deep roots in the country.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The white flight caused by the recession put the Rhodesian Army at a major disadvantage in its war against the black guerrillas.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The war cost the Rhodesian government one million Rhodesian dollars per day by 1975, and the costs of the war threatened to bankrupt Rhodesia.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1979, Rhodesia signed the Lancaster House Agreement, which led to Black majority rule in 1980.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Price controls exacerbated the crisis in the US.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The system limited the price of "old oil", that which had already been discovered, while allowing newly discovered oil to be sold at a higher price, to encourage investment.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a result, old oil was withdrawn from the market, creating greater scarcity.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The rule also discouraged development of alternative energies.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The rule had been intended to promote oil exploration.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Scarcity was addressed by rationing, as in many countries.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Motorists faced long lines at gas stations beginning in summer 1972 and increasing by summer 1973.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A sign of the change caused by the crisis was that in 1974 the Exxon oil company replaced the General Motors corporation to be the largest corporation in the world, as measured by gross sales revenues.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Simon as the first Administrator of the Federal Energy Office, a short-term organization created to coordinate the response to the embargo.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Simon allocated states the same amount of domestic oil for 1974 that each had consumed in 1972, which worked for states whose populations were not increasing.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In other states, lines at gasoline stations were common.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The American Automobile Association reported that in the last week of February 1974, 20% of American gasoline stations had no fuel.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Odd–even rationing allowed vehicles with license plates having an odd number as the last digit, or a vanity license plate, to buy gas only on odd-numbered days of the month.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Others could buy only on even-numbered days.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In some states, a three-color flag system was used to denote gasoline availability at service stations—green for unrationed availability, yellow for restricted/rationed sales, and red for out of stock.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Rationing led to violent incidents, when truck drivers chose to strike for two days in December 1973 over the limited supplies that Simon had allocated for their industry.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In Pennsylvania and Ohio, non-striking truckers were shot at by striking truckers.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In Arkansas, trucks of non-strikers were attacked with bombs.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America had controlled the price of natural gas since the 1950s.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] With the inflation of the 1970s, the price was too low to encourage the search for new reserves.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America's natural gas reserves dwindled from 237 trillion in 1974 to 203 trillion in 1978.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The price controls were not changed, despite president Gerald Ford's repeated requests to Congress.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] To help reduce consumption, in 1974 a national maximum speed limit of 55 mph (89 km/h) was imposed through the Emergency Highway Energy Conservation Act.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Development of the Strategic Petroleum Reserve began in 1975, and in 1977 the cabinet-level Department of Energy was created, followed by the National Energy Act of 1978.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In November 1995, President Bill Clinton signed the National Highway Designation Act, ending the federal 55 mph speed limit, which allowed states to restore their prior maximum speed limit.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Year-round daylight saving time was implemented from January 6, 1974, to October 27, 1975, with a break between October 27, 1974, and February 23, 1975, when the country observed standard time.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Parents complained that it forced many children to travel to school before sunrise.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis prompted a call to conserve energy, most notably a campaign by the Advertising Council using the tagline "Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Many newspapers carried advertisements featuring cut-outs that could be attached to light switches, reading "Last Out, Lights Out: Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although not regulated by the new legislation, auto racing groups voluntarily began conserving.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1974, NASCAR reduced all race distances by 10%; the 24 Hours of Daytona and the 12 Hours of Sebring race were cancelled.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1975, the Energy Policy and Conservation Act was passed, leading to the creation of the Corporate Average Fuel Economy (CAFE) standards that required improved fuel economy for cars and light trucks.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1976, Congress created the Weatherization Assistance Program to help low-income homeowners and renters reduce their demand for heating and cooling through better insulation.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1980, domestic luxury cars with a 130-inch (3.3 m) wheelbase and gross weights averaging 4,500 pounds (2,041 kg) were no longer made.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The automakers had begun phasing out the traditional front engine/rear-wheel drive layout in compact cars in favor of lighter front engine/front-wheel drive designs.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A higher percentage of cars offered more efficient four-cylinder engines.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Domestic auto makers also began offering more fuel efficient diesel powered passenger cars as well.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The energy crisis led to greater interest in renewable energy, nuclear power and domestic fossil fuels.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 2013, Peter Grossman opined that American energy policies after the crisis became and remained dominated by crisis-mentality thinking, promoting expensive quick fixes and single-shot solutions that ignore market and technology realities.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] He wrote that instead of providing stable rules that support basic research while leaving plenty of scope for entrepreneurship and innovation, Congresses and presidents repeatedly backed policies which promised politically expedient solutions whose true prospects were doubtful.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Brazilian government implemented its Proálcool (pro-alcohol) project in 1975 that mixed ethanol with gasoline for automotive fuel.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Israel was one of the few countries unaffected by the embargo, since it could extract sufficient oil from the Sinai.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] But to supplement Israel's over-taxed power grid, Harry Zvi Tabor, the father of Israel's solar industry, developed the prototype for a solar water heater now used in over 90% of Israeli homes.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Western central banks decided to sharply cut interest rates to encourage growth, deciding that inflation was a secondary concern.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although this was the orthodox macroeconomic prescription at the time, the resulting stagflation surprised economists and central bankers.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The policy is now considered by some to have deepened and lengthened the adverse effects of the embargo.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Recent research claims that in the period after 1985 the economy became more resilient to energy price increases.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The price shock created large current account deficits in oil-importing economies.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A petrodollar recycling mechanism was created, through which OPEC surplus funds were channeled through the capital markets to the West to finance the current account deficits.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The functioning of this mechanism required the relaxation of capital controls in oil-importing economies.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] It marked the beginning of an exponential growth of Western capital markets.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In the United States in 1974, seven of the 15 top Fortune 500 companies were oil companies, falling to four in 2014.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis had a major impact on international relations and created a rift within NATO.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Some European nations and Japan sought to disassociate themselves from United States foreign policy in the Middle East to avoid being targeted by the boycott.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Arab oil producers linked any future policy changes to peace between the belligerents.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] To address this, the Nixon Administration began multilateral negotiations with the combatants.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] They arranged for Israel to pull back from the Sinai Peninsula and the Golan Heights.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By January 18, 1974, US Secretary of State Henry Kissinger had negotiated an Israeli troop withdrawal from parts of the Sinai Peninsula.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The promise of a negotiated settlement between Israel and Syria was enough to convince Arab oil producers to lift the embargo in March 1974. and again during the 1979 energy crisis.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America's Cold War policies suffered a major blow from the embargo.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] They had focused on China and the Soviet Union, but the latent challenge to US hegemony coming from the Third World became evident.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 2004, declassified documents revealed that the US was so distraught by the rise in oil prices and being challenged by underdeveloped countries that they briefly considered military action to forcibly seize Middle Eastern oilfields in late 1973.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Western Europe began switching from pro-Israel to more pro-Arab policies.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] This change strained the Western alliance.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The US, which imported only 12% of its oil from the Middle East (compared with 80% for the Europeans and over 90% for Japan), remained staunchly committed to Israel.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The percentage of US oil which comes from the nations bordering the Persian Gulf remained steady over the decades, with a figure of a little more than 10% in 2008.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] With the embargo in place, many developed countries altered their policies regarding the Arab-Israeli conflict.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] These included the UK, which refused to allow the United States to use British bases and Cyprus to airlift resupplies to Israel, along with the rest of the members of the European Community.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Canada shifted towards a more pro-Arab position after displeasure was expressed towards Canada's mostly neutral position.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] "On the other hand, after the embargo the Canadian government moved quickly indeed toward the Arab position, despite its low dependence on Middle Eastern oil".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although lacking historical connections to the Middle East, Japan was the country most dependent on Arab oil.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] 71% of its imported oil came from the Middle East in 1970.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] On November 7, 1973, the Saudi and Kuwaiti governments declared Japan a "nonfriendly" country, to encourage it to change its noninvolvement policy.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] It received a 5% production cut in December, causing a panic.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] On November 22, Japan issued a statement "asserting that Israel should withdraw from all of the 1967 territories, advocating Palestinian self-determination, and threatening to reconsider its policy toward Israel if Israel refused to accept these preconditions".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By December 25, Japan was considered an Arab-friendly state.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil embargo was announced roughly one month after a right-wing military coup in Chile led by General Augusto Pinochet toppled socialist president Salvador Allende on September 11, 1973.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The response of the Nixon administration was to propose doubling arms sales.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a consequence, an opposing Latin American bloc was organized and financed in part by Venezuelan oil revenues, which quadrupled between 1970 and 1975.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil shock disrupted the status quo relationships between Arab countries and the US and USSR.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] At the time, Egypt, Syria and Iraq were allied with the USSR.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia, Turkey and Iran, plus Israel, aligned with the US.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Vacillations in alignment often resulted in greater support from the respective superpowers.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] When Anwar Sadat became president of Egypt in 1970, he dismissed Soviet specialists in Egypt and reoriented towards the US.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Concerns over economic domination from increased Soviet oil production turned into fears of military aggression after the 1979 Soviet invasion of Afghanistan, a major turning point in Cold War geopolitics.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Persian Gulf states turned toward the US for security guarantees against Soviet military action, coming at a time marked by increased American weapons sales, technology, and outright military presence to various US-allied nations.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia and Iran became increasingly dependent on American security assurances to manage both external and internal threats, including increased military competition between them over increased oil revenues.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Both states were competing for preeminence in the Persian Gulf, and using increased revenues to fund expanded militaries.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1979, Saudi arms purchases from the US were five times larger than Israel's.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia is a near-absolute monarchy, an Arabic speaking country, and has a Sunni Muslim majority, while Persian speaking Iran since 1979 is an Islamist theocracy with a Shiite Muslim majority, which explains the current hostility between Saudi Arabia and Iran.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil crisis sent a signal to the auto industry globally, which changed many aspects of production and usage for decades to come.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] After World War II, most West European countries taxed motor fuel to limit imports, and as a result most cars made in Europe were smaller and more economical than their American counterparts.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By the late 1960s, increasing incomes supported rising car sizes.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil crisis pushed West European car buyers away from larger, less economical cars.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The most notable result of this transition was the rise in popularity of compact hatchbacks.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The only notable small hatchbacks built in Western Europe before the oil crisis were the Peugeot 104, Renault 5 and Fiat 127.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By the end of the decade, the market had expanded with the introduction of the Ford Fiesta, Opel Kadett (sold as the Vauxhall Astra in Great Britain), Chrysler Sunbeam and Citroën Visa.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Buyers looking for larger cars were increasingly drawn to medium-sized hatchbacks.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Virtually unknown in Europe in 1973, by the end of the decade they were gradually replacing sedans as the mainstay of this sector.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Between 1973 and 1980, medium-sized hatchbacks were launched across Europe: the Chrysler/Simca Horizon, Fiat Ritmo (Strada in the UK), Ford Escort MK3, Renault 14, Volvo 340 / 360, Opel Kadett, and Volkswagen Golf.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] These cars were considerably more economical than the traditional saloons they were replacing, and attracted buyers who traditionally bought larger vehicles.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Some 15 years after the oil crisis, hatchbacks dominated most European small and medium car markets, and had gained a substantial share of the large family car market.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Before the energy crisis, large, heavy, and powerful cars were popular.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1971, the standard engine in a Chevrolet Caprice was a 400-cubic inch (6.5 liter) V8.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The wheelbase of this car was 121.5 inches (3,090 mm), and *Motor Trend*'s 1972 road test of the similar Chevrolet Impala achieved no more than 15 highway miles per gallon.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In the 15 years prior to the 1973 oil crisis, gasoline prices in the US had lagged well behind inflation.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis reduced the demand for large cars.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Japanese imports became mass-market leaders with unibody construction and front-wheel drive, which became de facto standards.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] From Europe, the Volkswagen Beetle, the Volkswagen Fastback, the Renault 8, the Renault LeCar, and the Fiat Brava were successful.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Detroit responded with the Ford Pinto, the Ford Maverick, the Chevrolet Vega, the Chevrolet Nova, the Plymouth Valiant and the Plymouth Volaré.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] American Motors sold its homegrown Gremlin, Hornet and Pacer models.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A decade after the 1973 oil crisis, Honda, Toyota and Nissan, affected by the 1981 voluntary export restraints, opened US assembly plants and established their luxury divisions (Acura, Lexus and Infiniti, respectively) to distinguish themselves from their mass-market brands.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Compact trucks were introduced, such as the Toyota Hilux and the Datsun Truck, followed by the Mazda Truck (sold as the Ford Courier), and the Isuzu-built Chevrolet LUV.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mitsubishi rebranded its Forte as the Dodge D-50 a few years after the oil crisis.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mazda, Mitsubishi and Isuzu had joint partnerships with Ford, Chrysler, and GM, respectively.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Later, the American makers introduced their domestic replacements (Ford Ranger, Dodge Dakota and the Chevrolet S10/GMC S-15), ending their captive import policy.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] An increase in imported cars into North America forced General Motors, Ford and Chrysler to introduce smaller and fuel-efficient models for domestic sales.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Dodge Omni / Plymouth Horizon from Chrysler, the Ford Fiesta and the Chevrolet Chevette all had four-cylinder engines and room for at least four passengers by the late 1970s.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1985, the average American vehicle moved 17.4 miles per gallon, compared to 13.5 in 1970.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The improvements stayed, even though the price of a barrel of oil remained constant at $12 from 1974 to 1979.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Sales of large sedans for most makes, except Chrysler products, recovered within two model years of the 1973 crisis.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Cadillac DeVille and Fleetwood, Buick Electra, Oldsmobile 98, Lincoln Continental, Mercury Marquis, and various other luxury oriented sedans became popular again in the mid-1970s.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The only full-size models that did not recover were lower price models such as the Chevrolet Bel Air and Ford Galaxie 500.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Slightly smaller models such as the Oldsmobile Cutlass, Chevrolet Monte Carlo, Ford Thunderbird and various others sold well.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Economical imports succeeded alongside heavy, expensive vehicles.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1976, Toyota sold 346,920 cars (average weight around 2,100 lbs), while Cadillac sold 309,139 cars (average weight around 5,000 lbs).
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Federal safety standards, such as NHTSA Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard 215 (pertaining to safety bumpers), and compacts like the 1974 Mustang I were a prelude to the DOT "downsize" revision of vehicle categories.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1977, GM's full-sized cars reflected the crisis.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1979, virtually all "full-size" American cars had shrunk, featuring smaller engines and smaller outside dimensions.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Chrysler ended production of their full-sized luxury sedans at the end of the 1981 model year, moving instead to a full front-wheel drive lineup for 1982, except for the M-body Dodge Diplomat/Plymouth Gran Fury and Chrysler New Yorker Fifth Avenue sedans.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] OPEC soon lost its preeminent position, and in 1981, its production was surpassed by that of other countries.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Additionally, its own member nations were divided.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia, trying to recover market share, increased production, pushing prices down, shrinking or eliminating profits for high-cost producers.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The world price, which had peaked during the 1979 energy crisis at nearly $40 per barrel, decreased during the 1980s to less than $10 per barrel.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Adjusted for inflation, oil briefly fell back to pre-1973 levels.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] This "sale" price was a windfall for oil-importing nations, both developing and developed.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] During the Iran–Iraq War of 1980–1988, the stated war aim of Iran was to overthrow the Baath regime in Iraq.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a consequence, Saudi Arabia and the other Arab Gulf states leaned in a very pro-Iraqi neutrality during the war.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a part of its policy of supporting Iraq, Saudi Arabia pumped out oil in massive quantities to lower the price as a way of hurting Iran's economy.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The low price of oil also hurt Iraq's economy, which forced Iraq to borrow massive sums of money, putting Iraq deeply into debt.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In contrast, Iran refused to borrow any money because of its refusal to pay interest on any loans, and paid the costs of the war directly from the sale of its oil.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Iran's revenue from the sale of oil went from $20 billion US dollars per year in 1982 to $5 billion US dollars per year by 1988, which pushed Iran to the verge of bankruptcy and forced Iran to make peace with Iraq later in 1988.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] During the war, the Iranian delegation at OPEC tried very hard to have the group cut production to raise prices, but were blocked by the other delegations led by the Saudi delegation, who insisted on more oil production.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The embargo encouraged new venues for energy exploration, including Alaska, the North Sea, the Caspian Sea, and the Caucasus.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Exploration in the Caspian Basin and Siberia became profitable.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Cooperation changed into a far more adversarial relationship as the USSR increased its production.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1980, the Soviet Union had become the world's largest producer.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Part of the decline in prices and economic and geopolitical power of OPEC came from the move to alternative energy sources.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] OPEC had relied on price inelasticity to maintain high consumption, but had underestimated the extent to which conservation and other sources of supply would eventually reduce demand.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Electricity generation from nuclear power and natural gas, home heating from natural gas, and ethanol-blended gasoline all reduced the demand for oil.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The drop in prices presented a serious problem for oil-exporting countries in northern Europe and the Persian Gulf.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Heavily populated, impoverished countries, whose economies were largely dependent on oil—including Mexico, Nigeria, Algeria, and Libya—did not prepare for a market reversal that left them in sometimes desperate situations.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] When reduced demand and increased production glutted the world market in the mid-1980s, oil prices plummeted and the cartel lost its unity.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mexico (a non-member), Nigeria, and Venezuela, whose economies had expanded in the 1970s, faced near-bankruptcy, and even Saudi Arabian economic power was significantly weakened.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The divisions within OPEC made concerted action more difficult.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As of 2015, OPEC has never approached its earlier dominance.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] The **1979 oil crisis**, sometimes referred to as the **second oil crisis** (in reference to the 1973 oil crisis), refers to the drop in oil production in the aftermath of the Iranian Revolution that led to an energy crisis in 1979.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Although the global oil supply only decreased by approximately four percent, the oil markets' reaction raised the price of crude oil drastically over the next 12 months, more than doubling it to $39.50 per barrel ($248/m3), equivalent to $175 per barrel ($1,101/m3) in 2025.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] The sudden increase in price was connected with fuel shortages similar to the 1973 oil crisis.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] In 1980, following the onset of the Iran–Iraq War, oil production in Iran fell drastically.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Iraq's oil production also dropped significantly, triggering economic recessions worldwide.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Oil prices did not return to pre-crisis levels until the mid-1980s.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Oil prices after 1980 began a steady decline over the next 20 years, except for a brief uptick during the Gulf War, which then reached a 60% fall-off in the 1990s.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Mexico, Nigeria, and Venezuela's major oil exporters expanded their production during this time.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] The Soviet Union became the largest oil producer in the world, and oil from the North Sea and Alaska flooded the market.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] In November 1978, a strike by 37,000 workers at Iran's nationalized oil refineries reduced production from 6 million barrels (950,000 m3) per day to about 1.5 million barrels (240,000 m3).
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] By bringing navy personnel into crude oil production operations, the government fixed short-term disruptions and by end of November the output came back to almost normal level.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] On January 16, 1979, the Shah of Iran, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, and his wife, Farah Pahlavi, left Iran at the behest of Prime Minister Shapour Bakhtiar, who sought to calm the situation.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] After the departure of the Shah, Ayatollah Khomeini became the new leader of Iran.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] The rise in oil prices benefited a few members of the Organization of Petroleum-Exporting Countries (OPEC), which made record profits.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Under the new Iranian government, oil exports later resumed but production was inconsistent and at a lower volume, further raising prices.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Saudi Arabia and other OPEC nations, under the presidency of Mana Al Otaiba, increased production to offset most of the decline, and by early 1979 the overall loss in worldwide production was roughly four percent.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] The war between Iran and Iraq in 1980 caused a further 7 percent drop in worldwide production.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] OPEC production was surpassed by other exporters such as the United States, as OPEC member nations were divided amongst themselves.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Saudi Arabia, a "swing producer", tried to gain back the market share after 1985, increasing production and causing downward pressure on prices, making high-cost oil production facilities less profitable.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] The oil crisis had a mixed impact on the United States.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Richard Nixon had imposed price controls on domestic oil as a result of the 1973 oil crisis.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Since then, gasoline price controls had been repealed, but those on domestic oil remained.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] The Jimmy Carter administration began a phased deregulation of oil prices on April 5, 1979, when the average price of crude oil was US$15.85 per barrel ($100/m3).
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Starting with the Iranian revolution, the price of crude oil rose to $39.50 per barrel ($248/m3) over the next 12 months (its all-time highest real price until March 3, 2008).
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Deregulating domestic oil price controls allowed U.S. oil output to rise sharply from the large Prudhoe Bay fields, while oil imports fell sharply.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Although not directly related, the near-disaster at Three Mile Island on March 28, 1979, also increased anxiety about energy policy and availability.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Due to memories of the oil shortage in 1973, motorists soon began panic buying, and long lines appeared at gas stations, as they had six years earlier.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] The average vehicle of the time consumed between two and three liters (about 0.5–0.8 gallons) of gasoline an hour while idling, and it was estimated that Americans wasted up to 150,000 barrels (24,000 m3) of oil per day idling their engines in the lines at gas stations.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] In 1979, the amount of oil sold in the United States was only 3.5 percent less than the record set for oil sold in 1978.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] A telephone poll of 1,600 American adults conducted by the Associated Press and NBC News and released in early May 1979 found that only 37 percent of Americans thought the energy shortages were real, nine percent were not sure, and 54 percent thought the energy shortages were a hoax.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Many politicians proposed gas rationing.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] One such proponent was Harry Hughes, Governor of Maryland, who proposed odd-even rationing (only people with an odd-numbered license plate could purchase gas on an odd-numbered day), as was used during the 1973 Oil Crisis.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Several states implemented odd-even gas rationing, including California, Pennsylvania, New York, New Jersey, Oregon, and Texas.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Coupons for gasoline rationing were printed but were never actually used during the 1979 crisis.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] On July 15, 1979, President Carter outlined his plans to reduce oil imports and improve energy efficiency in his "Crisis of Confidence" speech, sometimes known as the "malaise" speech.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] In the speech, Carter encouraged citizens to do what they could to reduce their use of energy.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] He had already installed water tank heating solar panels on the roof of the White House and a wood-burning stove in the living quarters.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] The panels were removed in 1986, reportedly for roof maintenance, during the administration of his successor, Ronald Reagan.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] A speech Carter gave in April 1977 argued that the oil crisis was "the moral equivalent of war".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] In November 1979, Iranian revolutionaries seized the American Embassy, and Carter imposed an embargo on Iranian oil.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] In January 1980, he issued the Carter Doctrine, declaring: "An attempt by any outside force to gain control of the Persian Gulf region will be regarded as an assault on the vital interests of the United States".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Additionally, as part of his administration's efforts at deregulation, Carter proposed removing price controls that had been imposed by the Richard Nixon administration before the 1973 crisis.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Carter agreed to remove price controls in phases.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] They were fully dismantled in 1981 under Reagan.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Carter also said he would impose a windfall profit tax on oil companies.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] While the regulated price of domestic oil was kept to $6 a barrel, the world market price was $30.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] In 1980, the U.S. government established the Synthetic Fuels Corporation to produce an alternative to imported fossil fuels.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] When the price of West Texas Intermediate crude oil increased 250 percent between 1978 and 1980, the oil-producing areas of Texas, Oklahoma, Louisiana, Colorado, Wyoming, and Alaska began experiencing an economic boom and population inflows.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] According to a 2019 study, individuals who were between the ages of 15 and 18 during the 1979 oil crisis were substantially less likely to use cars once they were in their mid-30s.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] In response to the high oil prices of the 1970s, industrial nations took steps to reduce their dependence on the Organization of Petroleum-Exporting Countries (OPEC) oil.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Electric utilities worldwide switched from oil to coal, natural gas, or nuclear power.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] National governments initiated multibillion-dollar research programs to develop alternatives to oil and commercial exploration developed major non-OPEC oilfields in Siberia, Alaska, North Sea, and the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] By 1986, daily worldwide demand for oil dropped by 5 million barrels but, non-OPEC production rose by an even-larger amount.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Consequently, OPEC's market share reduced from 50 percent in 1979 to 29 percent in 1985.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] At the time, Detroit's "Big Three" automakers (Ford, Chrysler, GM) were marketing downsized full-sized automobiles like the Chevrolet Caprice, the Ford LTD Crown Victoria and the Dodge St.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Regis which met the CAFE fuel economy mandates passed in 1978.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Detroit's response to the growing popularity of imported compacts like the Toyota Corolla and the Volkswagen Rabbit was the Chevrolet Citation and the Ford Fairmont.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Ford replaced the Ford Pinto with the Ford Escort and Chrysler, on the verge of bankruptcy, introduced the Dodge Aries K.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] GM was having unfavorable market reactions to the Citation and introduced the Chevrolet Corsica and Chevrolet Beretta in 1987 which sold better.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] GM also replaced the Chevrolet Monza, introducing the 1982 Chevrolet Cavalier which was better received.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Ford experienced a similar market rejection of the Fairmont and introduced the front-wheel-drive Ford Tempo in 1984.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Detroit was not well prepared for the sudden rise in fuel prices, and imported brands, primarily the Asian models, which were mass-marketed and had a lower manufacturing cost as opposed to British and West German brands.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] A year after the 1979 Iranian Revolution, Japanese manufacturers surpassed Detroit's production totals, becoming first in the world.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] The share of Japanese cars in U.S. auto purchases rose from 9 percent in 1976 to 21 percent in 1980.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Japanese exports later displaced the automotive market once dominated by lower-tier European manufacturers (Renault, Fiat, Opel, Peugeot, MG, Triumph, Citroen).
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Triumph, Simca) or withdraw from the U.S. market, especially in the wake of grey market automobiles or the inability of the vehicle to meet DOT requirements, from emission requirements to automotive lighting.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Many imported brands utilized fuel-saving technologies such as fuel injection and multi-valve engines over the common use of carburetors.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] The overall fuel economy of cars in the United States increased from about 15 miles per US gallon (16 L/100 km; 18 mpg‑imp) in 1979 to 18 mpg‑US (13 L/100 km; 22 mpg‑imp) by 1985 and 20 mpg‑US (12 L/100 km; 24 mpg‑imp) by 1990.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] This was one factor leading to the subsequent 1980s oil glut.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Acura was the first luxury division established by a Japanese automaker.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The creation of Acura coincided with the introduction of a JDM Honda dealership sales channel, called Honda Clio, which sold luxury vehicles, joining previously established Honda Verno, followed by Honda Primo the following year.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] In its first few years of existence, Acura was among the best-selling luxury marques in the US, outselling established brands such as BMW and Mercedes-Benz.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Though sales were down in the mid-to-late 1990s, the brand experienced a revival in the early 2000s, due to drastic redesigns and the introductions of new models.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] In the late 1980s, the success of the company's first flagship vehicle, the Legend, inspired fellow Japanese automakers Toyota and Nissan to launch their own luxury brands, Lexus and Infiniti, respectively.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The 1990 launch of the NSX, a mid-engine exotic sports car, offered a reliable and practical alternative to exotic European sports cars, and introduced Honda's VTEC variable valve timing system to the North American market.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The 1993 Legend coupé featured Acura's first use of a six-speed manual transmission mated to a Type II engine.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] In the late 1990s, Acura produced a Type R version of its compact Integra, which featured a reduced curb weight, a stiffer and lower suspension, and a high-output VTEC engine.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] In the early 2000s, Acura introduced new models, including the company's first all-original SUV, the MDX, and two models which replaced the Integra coupé and sedan, the RSX and TSX, respectively.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Type-S versions of the RSX, CL, and TL were added to the brand's lineup during that decade.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Acura's 2005 RL flagship introduced SH-AWD, a torque-vectoring all-wheel drive system.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The 2007 RDX, a crossover SUV, featured the first North American use of a turbocharged Honda engine.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] A second generation NSX was launched in 2016 and features a twin-turbocharged mid-engine, a nine-speed dual-clutch transmission, and Sport Hybrid SH-AWD.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Two more models were introduced in the mid-2010s—the TLX, which replaced both the TL and TSX, and the RLX, a new flagship.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] In the 2020s, the Type-S marque returned after a long hiatus, and the Integra and ZDX nameplates were revived; the latter is Acura's first electric vehicle.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The Acura name is derived from the Latin “**acu**tus,” meaning "to sharpen".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The logo is derived from the caliper, a precise design tool representing the meticulous attention to detail that goes into every car.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] It also closely resembles Honda's "H" logo, with the tops of the side verticals pinched together.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The brand was created around the same time as Japanese rivals Nissan and Toyota developed their respective Infiniti and Lexus premium brands.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The Japanese government imposed voluntary export restraints for the U.S. market, so it was more profitable for Japanese automakers to export more expensive cars to the U.S.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Following a decade of research, Honda opened 60 new dealerships in North America by 1986, to support its Acura automobile division.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Acura was the first Japanese luxury brand, introduced under the slogan, "Acura.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Precision Crafted Automobiles." Its initial offering consisted of two models: the executive class Legend and the compact class Integra, available as a five-door and three-door hatchback.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The Legend was the result of Project XX, a joint venture Honda entered into with the UK's Austin Rover Group.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] It was mechanically related to the Rover 800 series, while the Integra was an improvement of the Honda Quint hatchback.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Toyota introduced the Lexus ES, Nissan introduced the Infiniti J30 and Ford utilized the Taurus platform and named their new sedan the Lincoln Continental.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] In 1987, Acura's first full year of sales, they sold 109,000 cars with the flagship Legend sedan accounting for 55,000 sales and the rest were of the smaller Integra.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] By 1990, Acura was selling 138,000 vehicles, including 54,000 Legends, compared to Mercedes-Benz's 78,000 cars and 64,000 each for BMW and Lexus.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] In 1990, five years after the debut of the Legend and Integra, Acura introduced the NSX, a midship V6 powered, rear-wheel-drive sports car.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The NSX, an acronym for "New Sports eXperimental", was billed as the first Japanese car capable of competing with Ferrari and Porsche.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] This vehicle served as an "image car" for both the Honda and Acura brands, heralding the introduction of Honda's VTEC technology.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The NSX was the world's first all-aluminum production car, and was also marketed and viewed by some as the "everyday supercar" thanks in part to its ease of use, quality and reliability, traits that were unheard of in the supercar segment at the time.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] With the release of the NSX, Acura introduced the "A-badge", a stylized pair of calipers—a tool used for exacting measurements to imply that Acura vehicles are built to precise and demanding standards.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Despite a strong start in market acceptance for the Acura brand, sales suffered in the mid-to-late 1990s.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Some critics attributed this decline in part to less inspiring designs, which were re-branded Japanese-spec Hondas, such as the Acura Vigor in 1992.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Additionally, during this time Acura switched to an alphanumeric nomenclature formula, dropping the Legend, Vigor and Integra titles, following the lead of the NSX sportscar.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The parent company, Honda, was also feeling the results of the decline of the Japanese economy, due to the Japanese asset price bubble that took place during the 1990s and into the 2000s.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] This period is known in Japan as the Lost Decade.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] During this time, the NSX also lost sales as Acura made few changes from its original 1990 trim.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] A year later, the Integra sedan was withdrawn from the Canadian market, replaced by the market-exclusive Acura 1.6 EL, a rebadged Honda Civic/Domani.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The Integra sedan continued to be sold in the United States until 2001 (in name only, the model it was replaced with, the RSX, was simply a rebadged left-hand-drive version of the JDM DC5 Honda Integra).
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Despite these letdowns, Acura gained prominence in the 1990s with a young group of customers: "tuner" enthusiasts.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Parent company Honda's reputation with this demographic as a maker of "easy-to-tune" and "rev-happy" engines rubbed off onto Acura, and the Integra became a popular tuner car.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Beginning around the year 2000, Acura experienced a rebirth which was catalyzed by the introduction of several redesigned models.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The first of these models was the 1999 Acura 3.2 TL, an upscale sedan.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Critics suggested that although 3.2 TL did not outdo its competition in any one area of luxury cars, it offered a well-rounded blend of sportiness and luxury.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] These characteristics, combined with the TL's competitive price, proved very popular with consumers.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Subsequent Acura models have followed a similar philosophy of offering much standard equipment and few options.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Another refreshed Acura introduced in the early 2000s was the MDX, a popular three-row crossover SUV based on the Honda Odyssey minivan.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The MDX replaced the slow-selling SLX, which was little more than a rebadged Isuzu Trooper.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The MDX was a car-like crossover SUV with limited off-road capability that catered to the demands of the luxury SUV market.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] It was given top honors by Car and Driver in its first comparison test against seven other SUVs.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Other cars in Acura's line-up during this time included the 3.2 TL, 3.2 CL, RSX (formerly the Integra hatchback), and the NSX.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] By the late 2000s, Acura had dropped the inclusion of engine displacement numbers in its vehicle designations, retaining a simpler, two- or three-letter designation instead (e.g.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The 1999-2003 TL have been plagued by transmission and other problems.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] In 2001, a new coupe, badged as the RSX was introduced to the Acura line up.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] It was a replacement for the outgoing Integra.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The RSX is a rebadged Honda Integra (DC5) from the Japanese market.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] As a result, the RSX is technically a new generation of the outgoing Integra.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Much like the Integra, the RSX was a hit in the tuner market.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] However, at the end of 2006, the RSX was taken out of the Acura line up, subsequently in the Japanese market as well.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] It is not known why the RSX did not continue to be sold as the Integra in Japan, however, the reason that Acura gave for the cancellation of the RSX is that Acura wishes to move up in the luxury brand, thus cannot sell a car that is mostly driven by teenagers.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] A new TL was introduced for the 2004 model year, with a 270 hp (200 kW) V6 measured by the then-current SAE standards.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The new TL increased sales dramatically to 70,943 American units in 2005.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Also around the same time the Acura TSX was introduced.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] It was essentially a re-badged European and Japanese market Honda Accord loaded with features.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] This model became the only 4-cylinder sedan in Acura's line-up (with the exception of the Canadian market Acura CSX, which replaced the EL in 2006).
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Acura's new models—particularly the TL and TSX—were well received by the motoring press and became Acura's top selling vehicles by then.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The TSX was on *Car and Driver*'s Ten Best list from 2004 to 2006.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] In 2005, a new RL was introduced with a 300 hp (220 kW) V6, improved styling, and Super Handling All-Wheel Drive (SH-AWD), a system capable of sending almost all of the RL's power to just one wheel in a turn.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The second-generation RL appeared on *Car and Driver*'s Ten Best list for 2005, and also garnered an CNET.com "Editor's Choice".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] However in the midsize luxury segment, RL sales lagged far behind not only the best-selling German offerings but also Japanese contemporaries like the Lexus GS and Infiniti M.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Honda Japan had set the RL's initial price high, close to those with V8 engines, disappointing potential customers who perceived Acura as not being on par with its German rivals in brand equity and expected more value from the Japanese marque.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The damage from Honda Japan's alleged hubris was done, even though Honda Canada has since reduced the RL's price.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] In 2006 Acura introduced a compact crossover SUV which was based on its own unique unibody chassis called the RDX with models becoming available to U.S. consumers in August 2006.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] It is powered by a turbocharged 240-hp 4-cylinder engine and, like the RL, uses Acura's SH-AWD system.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] A completely redesigned MDX became available in the fall of 2006 with a 300 hp (220 kW) V6 engine and Super Handling All-Wheel Drive.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Acura reintroduced the TL Type-S for the 2007 model year.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] 2009 marked the all new TL and TSX models as well as a mid-year model update for the RL; all three made their debuts in the 2008 calendar year.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Acura planned on redesigning the RL by 2011 as well as announced the creation of a brand new luxury crossover vehicle called the ZDX, previewed by the concept of the same name.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The ZDX was the first vehicle designed in Acura's design studio located in Torrance, California.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The ZDX was designed by Michelle Christensen, and based on the Acura MDX using that vehicle's 3.7 litre V6 engine (300 bhp) and SH-AWD system.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] It is also the first Acura to be completely built in North America.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The production model of the ZDX made its debut in the Orange County Auto Show in Southern California on 15 October 2009.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The concept behind the ZDX is that it is a "four door coupe," and the design emphasis of the body of the car is like a "pulled back slingshot." Another prominent design aspect of the ZDX is the wide rear shoulders above the rear wheels.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Acura initially had plans for the third generation of RL to be a rear wheel drive V8 sedan for its flagship, but shelved the plans in the wake of the 2008 economic downturn.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Acura announced new TSX wagon in the 2010 New York Auto Show and went on sale in Fall of 2010.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The wagon version of the TSX is based on the wagon version of the Euro-spec Honda Accord which has been in the European market for some time.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] However, Acura did not announce any plans for the third-generation RL.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] For the 2010 model year the MDX models received some slight exterior changes and increased equipment levels.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Mechanically the engine remained unchanged but the transmission was updated from the previous 5-speeds to 6-speeds including steering column mounted shift override paddles.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] This new transmission was shared with the ZDX.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] In 2012, Acura introduced a new model called the ILX which replaced the Acura CSX in Canada and is based on the Honda Civic platform.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] It also unveiled the Acura RLX Concept, a replacement for the RL sedan, at the New York International Auto Show.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The ILX went on sale in May 2012 in the United States as a 2013 model.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Also in 2012, Acura "reinvented" another model, The RDX concept.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] For the new model, Acura dropped the 4 cylinder turbo for a 3.5L V6.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] When the official 2013 Acura RDX was released, it was relatively similar to the concept but had changes in wheels, taillights, and some other cosmetics.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] A lot of this Acura looks like its brother the ILX.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The 2013 RDX doesn't have the SH-AWD system instead it has "AWD with intelligent control", similar to the CR-V's AWD system.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] In 2013, Acura showed a 2014 Concept of the MDX.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Shortly after, it was released to the public.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The MDX competes with the Lexus RX, Audi Q7, and many others.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] In December 2013, at the Los Angeles Auto Show, Acura unveiled a Sport Hybrid SH-AWD version of the flagship RLX sedan.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] It has a 310-horsepower 3.5L V6 engine and a pair of electric motors (one for each axle) that generate a combined 377 horsepower through a new 7-speed dual clutch transmission.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The new RLX Sport Hybrid will go on sale in mid-2014.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] In January 2014, at the Detroit Auto Show, Acura unveiled the all-new 2015 TLX sports sedan.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] This new vehicle replaced the soon to be discontinued TSX and TL sedans.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The TLX in the 2.4-liter comes with Acura's all new eight-speed dual clutch DCT transmission.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Meanwhile, the high-end 3.5-liter V6 model came with the new nine-speed transmission and Super-Handling All Wheel Drive (SH-AWD).
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The TLX went on sale in the Summer of 2014.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] In 2015, Acura redesigned the ILX for the 2016 model year.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Now solely available with a 2.4L K24V7 engine and 8-speed dual clutch transmission (DCT) instead of the 2.0L R20A1 & 5-speed automatic transmission, 2.4L K24Z7 6 speed manual transmission and hybrid electric options.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Featured with the same 3.5L 6-speed automatic with some slight adjustments for efficiency and hp/torque boosts.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The RDX gets the Acura Jewel Eye LED treatment as well.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] A new Advance Package is being offered with the inclusion of, parking sensors (front and rear), rain-sensing windshield wipers, auto-dimming side mirrors, remote start, ventilated seats, and foglights.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] In 2017, Acura made considerations on opening an Indian branch.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Almost since its inception, Acura has been involved in American motorsports, specifically in Sports Car Club of America (SCCA) and IMSA GT Championship series.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Starting in 1991, Acura reached an agreement with Comptech Racing to use the V6 motor of the Acura NSX in Comptech's Camel Lights Spice prototype.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Acura would go on to take the Lights championship in its initial year, including a class win at the 24 Hours of Daytona.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Acura and Comptech would take the Lights championships again in 1992 and 1993, as well as another Daytona class win in 1992 and a class win at the 12 Hours of Sebring for 1993.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] However a change in the IMSA rules would lead to the demise of the Camel Lights, and so Acura moved to touring car racing, joining Realtime Racing in the SCCA World Challenge with the NSX in 1996, winning the final two races of the season.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] In 1997, Acura added Acura Integras to the lower classes, and were successful in taking the championship in both of these classes.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Realtime took the touring championship with the Integra again in 1998, and came within a few points of winning it again in 1999 only to lose it in the final race, then coming back to retake the title in 2000.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Although Realtime had abandoned the NSX program in 1998, the NSXs returned to the top class in 2001.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Although the NSX squad suffered mechanical woes and were unable to take the title, the Integras of the touring class once again took the teams championship.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] By 2002, Acura replaced the aged Integra with the RSX in the final races of the season, scoring good finishes in their debut.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] At the same time, Acura finally retired the NSXs from the top GT class.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The RSXs would later be joined by new Acura TSXs in 2004.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Realtime continues to campaign the RSX and TSX in the SCCA Speed World Challenge.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Acura also currently races RSXs and TSXs in the Grand American Road Racing Association's KONI Challenge Series for touring cars.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] At the Detroit Auto Show in 2006, Acura announced their plans to enter the American Le Mans Series with multiple teams of Le Mans prototypes in the LMP2 class starting in 2007 season.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The cars would be purchased chassis from existing manufacturers, but use American-built Acura V8s (a first for Acura and Honda).
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Acura also announced their initiative to take the cars to the 24 Hours of Le Mans in 2008 and eventually move to the superior LMP1 class with cars built by Acura themselves in 2009.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Later in 2006, Acura announced that the three factory teams would be Andretti Green Racing, Fernández Racing, and Highcroft Racing, and that the chassis would be built by Lola Cars of the UK and Courage Compétition of France.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The three Acura-powered prototypes debuted at the 2007 12 Hours of Sebring, which was the opening round of the ALMS season, and were successful in their debut.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Andretti Green's Acura took second place overall and first in the LMP2 class, while Fernández Racing took third overall, and Highcroft sixth, beating a series of established Porsche teams in their class.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] At the same time, Acura began development of their own chassis by heavily modifying their purchased Courage chassis.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The cars now have been so radically changed from their original orientation that they are now named Acura ARX-01a.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Acura will introduce evolved B-spec cars in the 2008 season, with Gil de Ferran launching a fourth Acura team in the ALMS.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] In 2009, Acura produced its first LMP1 car, the Acura ARX-02a.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] In 2010, Honda rebadged all Acura prototypes as Honda Performance Development (HPD) cars, and announced that all future prototypes (such as the HPD ARX-03) would be constructed under the HPD name.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Acura did not participate in motorsports again until 2013, where two Acura ILXs were unofficially entered in the 25 Hours of Thunderhill by Honda R&D Americas designers and engineers (Team Honda Research West).
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The car would retire from the race due to engine problems.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The Acura ILXs returned to Thunderhill for the 2014 25-hour race.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] This time the car won its class and finished 8th overall.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] At the 2016 New York International Auto Show, Acura announced the GT3 version of the NSX, which began competition in 2017 with factory support in both WeatherTech SportsCar Championship's GTD class and Pirelli World Challenge GT class, the latter replacing the Acura TLX.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The car competes under Honda branding outside North America.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The Acura logo, introduced in 1990 for the 1991 model year, is, according to Honda, a caliper — a design tool used for measuring that can also be interpreted as a skewed "H" (for Honda) or a stylised "A" (for Acura).
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The logo that was originally authorized without approval by Soichiro Honda did not contain the small horizontal bar joining the two vertical pillars—thus, it did not form the letter "H".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Soichiro Honda ordered the 5,000 badges already produced to be destroyed, including prying off the emblems applied to 309 cars already (US-spec Integra, Legend, and NSX models).
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Acura's current marketing slogan is "Precision Crafted Performance." Recent models include Technology, Advance, Type-S, SH-AWD and A-Spec trim levels.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Technology and Advance models typically come with the latest hi-tech features such as keyless start and a blind spot information system.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Type-S and SH-AWD models are performance-oriented, with a substantial increase in horsepower compared to the lower trim levels.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Some models, such as the TL, also combine trim levels (i.e.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Acura began an association with Marvel Entertainment in 2010, upon release of the film *Iron Man 2*, which featured a ZDX after the ending credits.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] On April 20, 2011, Acura and Marvel announced a promotional campaign, making Acura the official brand of Marvel's fictional S.H.I.E.L.D. organization.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Soon thereafter, several Acura models—such as the MDX, ZDX, RL, and TL—appeared in the films *Thor* and *Captain America: The First Avenger*.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] In the 2012 film, *The Avengers*, Iron Man (played by Robert Downey Jr.) drove an exotic sportscar by Acura, made specifically for the film, rather than the Audi R8 he previously drove.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] It was rumored that the car spotted during filming was a concept for the second generation NSX, however, a different-looking 2012 Acura NSX Concept was unveiled at the North American International Auto Show, on 9 January 2012.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] From 1995 to 2007, Acura sponsored two WTA Tour tennis tournaments, both named the Acura Classic.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] In 2012, Acura was the presenting sponsor and official vehicle of the Sundance Film Festival.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Acura also has a 'Mobility Program' that ensures drivers who are disabled are safe in their vehicles.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] The program offers cash reimbursement towards the cost of adaptive equipment for disabled drivers.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/acura] Acura was the official shirt sponsor of the Columbus Crew from 2017 to 2020.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] AGCO was established on June 20, 1990, when Robert J.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] Seaver, who were executives at Deutz-Allis, bought out Deutz-Allis North American operations from the parent corporation Klöckner-Humboldt-Deutz AG (KHD), a German company which owned the Deutz-Fahr brand of agriculture equipment.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] KHD had purchased portions of the Allis-Chalmers agricultural equipment business five years earlier.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] After the organization of the company, Robert Ratliff was selected to be the company's first chairman.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] The company was called Gleaner-Allis Corporation, then the name was changed to Allis-Gleaner Corporation, or AGCO.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] The Deutz-Allis line of tractors was renamed AGCO-Allis, and Gleaner became a brand of its own for combines.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] The Deutz-Allis brand continued in South America until 2001, when it was renamed AGCO-Allis.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In 2001, AGCO Allis was renamed AGCO in North America.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In March 1991, AGCO purchased the Hesston Corporation, which is in Hesston, Kansas, gaining hay and forage equipment as well as technologies such as the grain auger, invented in 1947 by Lyle Yost.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] Hesston had a 50 percent joint venture with Case International, now a part of CNH Global.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] AGCO purchased the White Tractor line from the Allied Corporation's White-New Idea company.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In 1993, AGCO purchased the remainder of White-New Idea, a manufacturer of New Idea hay equipment, manure spreaders, and White planters with a large manufacturing plant in Coldwater, Ohio.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] AGCO purchased the North American distribution rights to global agricultural equipment manufacturer Massey Ferguson in 1993 and purchased the company from Varity the following year.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] The acquisition of England-based Massey Ferguson gave AGCO access to markets in Europe and around the world.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] At the time, Massey Ferguson had 20 percent of the global market share for tractors.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] AGCO also purchased McConnell Tractors in 1994, manufacturer of the large articulated Massey Ferguson tractors.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] AGCO developed the Agcostar line of articulated tractors.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] Later in 1994, the Black Machine line of planters was purchased.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In 1995 AgEquipment Group was bought; it manufactured tillage equipment and loaders under the Glenco, Tye and Farmhand brands.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In 1996, acquisitions went international with the purchase of Iochpe-Maxion in Brazil.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] It was the Brazilian company which had rights to the Massey Ferguson brand and manufacturing in the region, as well as the *Maxion* brand of industrial equipment.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In the same year AGCO purchased Deutz Argentina, the number one leader of tractors in Argentina.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] Also in 1996, AGCO purchased Western Combine Corporation and Portage Manufacturing in Canada.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] Western Combine had previously purchased the assets of the Massey Combine Corporation's combine operation, which had been spun off by Massey Ferguson.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In 1997 the company purchased Fendt which is based in Germany, the German tractor company.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] The acquisition of Fendt was contingent on three conditions; 1) The Fendt name would be retained, 2) The factory in Marktoberdorf would continue to operate, and 3) a fair price would be paid for the company.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] Also in 1997, AGCO acquired Dronningborg Industries in Denmark, the manufacturer of European Massey Ferguson combines, and former manufacturer of Dronningborg combines.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In 1998, AGCO made a joint venture with Deutz AG to produce engines in Argentina, and purchased the Spra-Coupe and Willmar companies.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] Spra-Coupe and Willmar are sprayer companies in North America.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] SpraCoupe originated in Bismarck, North Dakota.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] After being purchased by AGCO, the manufacturing of SpraCoupes was moved to Willmar, Minnesota where the Willmar branded fertilizer tenders and "Wrangler" articulated loaders were being manufactured.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] SpraCoupe and Willmar products were manufactured in Willmar from 1998 to 2001.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In the year 2000, AGCO bought out its partner CNH Global N.V. in the Hay and Forage Industries joint venture.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In 2001, AGCO purchased Ag-Chem Equipment, expanding its application equipment business.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] Ag-Chem Equipment was based in Jackson, Minnesota, and developed the TerraGator flotation-type and RoGator rowcrop-type applicators.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] Also in 2001, the SpraCoupe and Willmar brands moved their manufacturing from Willmar, Minnesota, to the Jackson facility and the *Agco-Allis* and *White* tractor lines were merged in North America under the *AGCO* brand, continuing in the orange color.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In 2002, AGCO purchased rights to the Challenger name and the tracked tractors from the Caterpillar Corporation, giving the firm a well-known brand name and high-power tracked tractors.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] AGCO also purchased the Sunflower Manufacturing Company in Beloit, Kansas, which manufactures tillage, seeding, and specialty harvesting equipment.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In 2004, AGCO purchased the Valtra tractor company from the Kone Group, in Finland.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] The purchase of Valtra also included SISU Diesel engines..
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] Before that AGCO hadn't had its own engine factory, instead it used engines from eight different manufacturers.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] 2006 saw a re-focusing of the various brands and subsidiaries, and the reduction of individual brands.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] AGCO announced plans to combine some, and make some only part of a larger brand, or co-branding.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] Examples include the Massey Ferguson 9635 Hesston self-propelled swather, and the AGCO 9365 Hesston self-propelled swather.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] Challenger has seen further expansion with the further consolidation of the AgChem brand into Challenger, and the introduction of Agritalia built tractors and an articulated Challenger tractor.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In August 2006, AGCO saw its first change in the position of chairman since its founding with the selection of Martin Richenhagen to succeed Robert Ratliff.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In 2007, AGCO bought 50% of Laverda S.p.A. from ARGO SpA, which included the Gallagnani and Fella-Werke hay equipment brands.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In 2008/2009 AGCO, the Challenger, Valtra, and Massey Ferguson large row crop tractors were launched in Europe and North America respectively with AGCO's e3 Selective Catalytic Reduction (SCR) emission reduction technology.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] Late in 2009, the firm announced that it would phase out orange AGCO tractors by 2011.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In late 2010, the firm announced the plan to acquire the remaining 50% of Laverda, which included Fella-Werke as well.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] The acquisition was finalized in March 2011.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In 2011, the firm plans to transfer its assembly of high-horsepower wheeled tractors sold in North America from Beauvais, France to Jackson, Minnesota, where it will expand the plant by 75,000 square feet (7,000 m2).
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In 2011, the firm said that it will invest $40 million in its Hesston, Kansas plant with a new 200,000-square-foot (19,000 m2) painting and finishing building.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] Construction began June 2011 and was completed in 2013.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In October 2011, AGCO purchased GSI, based in Assumption, Illinois, a manufacturer of grain storage and handling equipment.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] AGCO acquired 60% of Santal Equipamentos, a sugar cane planting and harvesting equipment.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] It also purchased 80% of Shandong Dafeng Machinery Co, a combine harvester manufacturer in China.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] AGCO formed the Algerian Tractors Company joint venture with the Algerian brand Etrag with 49% ownership.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In 2013, GSI acquired Johnson System, based in Marshall, Michigan, a manufacturer of catwalks and towers.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In 2013, AGCO started Fuse Technologies, a smart farming technology division.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In 2016, AGCO acquired Cimbria, based in Thisted, Denmark, a processing, handling and storage of seed and grain business.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In 2017, AGCO acquired Precision Planting, based in Tremont, Illinois, a planting equipment and technology business.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In 2017, AGCO acquired the forage machinery line from Lely, including balers, loading wagons, mowers, tedders, rakes, and the rights to the entire portfolio of the defunct Mengele Agrartechnik.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] This included factories in Wolfenbuettel (D) and Waldstetten (D).
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] The factory in Maassluis (NL) will be closed in 2018.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In September 2020, AGCO acquired 151 Research Inc., a Winnipeg, Manitoba based company that specializes in grain storage research and development.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In 2021, AGCO named Eric Hansotia its third chairman, succeeding Richenhagen, who retired after approximately 15 years as head of the company.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] Hansotia has been working for AGCO since 2013 and became its chief operating officer in October 2018.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] The Trimble acquisition resulted in PTx Trimble, a joint venture between the companies for autonomizing and retrofitting farm equipment.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/agco] In July 2024 AGCO announced it had reached an agreement with private equity firm American Industrial Partners to divest its Grain and Protein divisions including GSI, Automated Production, Tecno, Cimbria, and Cumberland brands.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/am-general] AM General has also been a provider of vehicles for the CUCV program carried out by the United States Armed Forces.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/am-general] AM General traces its roots to the Standard Wheel Company of Terre Haute, Indiana, which expanded in 1903 to include the Overland Automotive Division.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/am-general] In 1908, John North Willys purchased the Overland company, then based in Indianapolis, Indiana, and renamed it Willys-Overland Motors.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/am-general] Army awarded a contract to Willys-Overland Motor Company to produce the Willys MB, also known as the Jeep, for the U.S.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/am-general] It then mass-produced that vehicle as "America's first four-wheel-drive, one-fourth-ton, tactical utility truck"—the Jeep of World War II fame.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/am-general] In 1953, Kaiser Motors purchased Willys-Overland, changing its name first to Kaiser-Willys Motor Company, and in 1963, to Kaiser-Jeep Corporation.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/am-general] In 1970, it was purchased by American Motors Corporation (AMC).
[src:checker-motors-corporation/am-general] In July 2020, KPS Capital Partners acquired the company.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/am-general] In 1964, Kaiser-Jeep purchased the Studebaker facilities on Chippewa Avenue in South Bend, Indiana, Studebaker's "General Products Division", and its substantial defense contracts.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/am-general] At the time, Kaiser had been awarded a US$87 million Army truck contract, and under government pressure, agreed to perform the work at the South Bend plant it had recently acquired from Studebaker.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/am-general] In 1970, American Motors Corporation (AMC) purchased the Jeep Corporation from Kaiser, when Kaiser decided to leave the auto business.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/am-general] In 1971, AMC made the General Products Division of Jeep (producing military trucks as well as contract and non-commercial vehicles) a wholly owned subsidiary and renamed it "AM General Corporation".
[src:checker-motors-corporation/am-general] In 1982, American Motors ceased to function as an independent automaker when Renault purchased a total 46.1% interest.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/am-general] Federal government regulations at that time forbade ownership of defense contractors by foreign governments — and the French government partially owned Renault.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/am-general] In 1983, LTV Corporation bought AM General and established it as a wholly owned subsidiary.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/am-general] In 1984, its headquarters moved from the American Motors AMTEK Building in Detroit, Michigan, to Livonia, Michigan, and two years later to South Bend, Indiana, where primary manufacturing operations were located.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/am-general] In 1992, AM General was sold to Renco Group, which in 2002 converted it to a limited liability company.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/am-general] In 1984, AM General built a factory for HMMWV production at 13200 McKinley Hwy in Mishawaka.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/am-general] In 1992, AM General began marketing the HMMWV to the civilian market under the Hummer brand.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/am-general] In 1999, GM acquired the rights to the brand and continued production of the original civilian Hummer as the H1 until June 2006.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/am-general] In 2002, the Hummer H2 went on the market and was produced until January 2009.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/am-general] It was designed and marketed by GM, and manufactured by AM General at the Mishawaka plant.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/am-general] GM was sued early in 2003 by DaimlerChrysler, owners of the Jeep brand, for the resemblance of the Hummer's seven-slot grille to Jeep's.
[src:checker-motors-corporation/am-general] The lawsuit was dismissed after acknowledgment of the shared corporate history of AMC and Jeep.
